ay]] \n*[[Upper LaHave, Nova Scotia|Upper LaHave]]\n*[[Middle La Have, Nova Scotia|Middle LaHave]]\n*[[East LaHave, Nova Scotia|East LaHave]]\n*[[Rose Bay, Nova Scotia|Rose Bay]]\n*[[Riverport, Nova Scotia|Riverport]]\n*[[Lunenburg, Nova Scotia|Lunenburg]]\n*[[Liverpool, Nova Scotia|Liverpool]]\n*[[Lockeport, Nova Scotia|Lockeport]]\n*[[Sable River, Nova Scotia|Sable River]]\n*[[Louis Head, Nova Scotia|Louis Head]]\n*[[Little Harbour, Shelburne, Nova Scotia|Little Harbour]]\n*[[Lockeport, Nova Scotia|Lockeport]]\n*[[East Green Harbour, Nova Scotia|East Green Harbour]]\n*[[East Jordan, Nova Scotia|East Jordan]]\n*[[Shelburne, Nova Scotia|Shelburne]]\n*[[Barrington Passage, Nova Scotia|Barrington Passage]]\n*[[Centreville, Shelburne, Nova Scotia|Centreville]]\n*[[Baccaro, Nova Scotia|Baccaro]]\n*[[Clyde River, Nova Scotia|Clyde River]]\n*[[Charlesville, Nova Scotia|Charlesville]]\n*[[Lower Woods Harbour, Nova Scotia|Lower Woods Harbour]]\n*[[Argyle, Nova Scotia|Argyle]]\n*[[Tusket, Nova Scotia|Tusket]]\n*[[Yarmouth, Nova Scotia|Yarmouth]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{NS Roads and Highways}}\n{{Coord|44|36|40.04|N|64|7|23.7|W|region:CA|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Scenic travelways in Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Roads in Halifax, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Roads in the Region of Queens Municipality]]\n[[Category:Roads in Shelburne County, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Roads in Lunenburg County, Nova Scotia]]\n[[Category:Roads in Yarmouth County, Nova Scotia]]\n", "name_user": "MuzikMachine", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lighthouse_Route"}
{"title_page": "Judith Nelson Dilday", "text_new": "{{short description|American lawyer and judge}}\n'''Judith Nelson Dilday''' (born 1943<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/>) is an American lawyer and the first person of color appointed as a judge of the Massachusetts Probate and Family Court.<ref name=\":0\" /><Ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/>\n\n==Education and personal life==\nDilday grew up in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.<ref name=banner/> Her grandparents were originally from Alabame but traveled north during the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]].<ref name=banner/>\n\nDilday studied French at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and was graduated in 1966.<ref name=banner/><ref name=martindale/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She earned several graduate credits in French at [[Millersville State College]].<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> After graduation, Dilday was a public school French teacher in Pittsburgh for four years before moving to Boston.<ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She went on to the [[Boston University School of Law]] and was graduated with the class of 1972.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=martindale/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> While in law school, she met her husband, James Dilday.<ref name=banner/> The couple went on to have children.<ref name=banner/>\n\n==Legal career==\n\nDilday began her career in private practice and in government service.<Ref name=bba/> She rose to become the first black president of the [[Women's Bar Association]] in 1990 to 1991.<ref name=bba/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She also worked in the law firm of Stern and Shapiro and then the [[Department of the Interior]]'s solicitor's office.<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> Dilday was a founding partner of Burnham, Hines & Dilday, the first law firm in [[New England]] owned by [[African American]] women.<ref name=aka/><ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She was also the first black woman to work in the Suffolk County District Attorney's office.<ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> \n\nDilday was appointed to the Probate and Family Court in 1993 as a circuit judge.<Ref name=bba/> At the time, she was one of only four black women on the Massachusetts bench.<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> In 1998, she was appointed as an Associate Justice in the Middlesex Probate and Family Court.<Ref name=bba/> Dilday retired in June 2009.<ref name=probate/>\n\nShe has run mock trials for Chinese law students and taught English in [[Qiqihar, China]].<ref name=banner/>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of first women lawyers and judges in Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/about/diversity/a-history-of-diversity/|title=A History of Diversity at BU Law {{!}} School of Law|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aka>{{cite web | url = http://akapioneers.aka1908.com/index.php/component/mtree/vocations/law-1/state-court-judge-2/2091-dilday-judith-nelson | title = Dilday, Judith Nelson | publisher = [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] Sorority | accessdate = April 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n<Ref name=banner>{{cite news | url = https://www.baystatebanner.com/2011/11/02/icing-on-the-cake/ | date = November 2, 2011 | accessdate = April 2, 2020 | title = \u2018Icing on the cake\u2019 | first = Jacquinn | last = Williams | newspaper = Bay State Banner }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bba>{{cite web| url = https://bostonbar.org/membership/events/event-details?ID=3296 | title = A Tribute to Judge Judith Nelson Dilday and Probation Officer Joseph O'Connor | accessdate = April 3, 2020 | publisher = Boston Bar Association }}</ref>\n\n<Ref name=martindale>{{Cite web | url = https://www.martindale.com/attorney/judith-nelson-dilday-666237/ | title = Judith Nelson Dilday | accessdate = April 3, 2020 | publisher = Martindale-Hubbell }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=probate>{{Cite news | url = https://masslawyersweekly.com/2011/05/18/probate-court-gets-new-judge-2/ | title = Probate Court gets new judge | first = Phillip |last =  Bantz | date = May 18, 2011 | accessdate = April 3, 2020 | newspaper = Massachusetts Lawyer's Weekly }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Smith2012\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Jessie Carney |title=Black Firsts: 4,000 Ground-Breaking and Pioneering Historical Events|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=steLXpuOONEC&pg=PT593|accessdate=April 3, 2020|date=December 1, 2012|publisher=Visible Ink Press|isbn=978-1-57859-425-2|page=593}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dilday, Judith Nelson}}\n\n[[Category:African-American judges]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts state court judges]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Educators from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Millersville State College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American lawyer and judge}}\n'''Judith Nelson Dilday''' (born 1943<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/>) is an American lawyer and the first person of color appointed as a judge of the Massachusetts Probate and Family Court.<ref name=\":0\" /><Ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/>\n\n==Education and personal life==\nDilday grew up in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania.<ref name=banner/> Her grandparents were originally from Alabame but traveled north during the [[Great Migration (African American)|Great Migration]].<ref name=banner/>\n\nDilday studied French at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] and was graduated in 1966.<ref name=banner/><ref name=martindale/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She earned several graduate credits in French at [[Millersville State College]].<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> After graduation, Dilday was a public school French teacher in Pittsburgh for four years before moving to Boston.<ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She went on to the [[Boston University School of Law]] and was graduated with the class of 1972.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=martindale/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> While in law school, she met her husband, James Dilday.<ref name=banner/> The couple went on to have children.<ref name=banner/>\n\n==Legal career==\n\nDilday began her career in private practice and in government service.<Ref name=bba/> She rose to become the first black president of the [[Women's Bar Assocation]] in 1990 to 1991.<ref name=bba/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She also worked in the law firm of Stern and Shapiro and then the [[Department of the Interior]]'s solicitor's office.<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> Dilday was a founding partner of Burnham, Hines & Dilday, the first law firm in [[New England]] owned by [[African American]] women.<ref name=aka/><ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> She was also the first black woman to work in the Suffolk County District Attorney's office.<ref name=banner/><ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> \n\nDilday was appointed to the Probate and Family Court in 1993 as a circuit judge.<Ref name=bba/> At the time, she was one of only four black women on the Massachusetts bench.<ref name=\"Smith2012\"/> In 1998, she was appointed as an Associate Justice in the Middlesex Probate and Family Court.<Ref name=bba/> Dilday retired in June 2009.<ref name=probate/>\n\nShe has run mock trials for Chinese law students and taught English in [[Qiqihar, China]].<ref name=banner/>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of first women lawyers and judges in Massachusetts]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|refs=\n\n<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bu.edu/law/about/diversity/a-history-of-diversity/|title=A History of Diversity at BU Law {{!}} School of Law|website=www.bu.edu|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=aka>{{cite web | url = http://akapioneers.aka1908.com/index.php/component/mtree/vocations/law-1/state-court-judge-2/2091-dilday-judith-nelson | title = Dilday, Judith Nelson | publisher = [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] Sorority | accessdate = April 2, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n<Ref name=banner>{{cite news | url = https://www.baystatebanner.com/2011/11/02/icing-on-the-cake/ | date = November 2, 2011 | accessdate = April 2, 2020 | title = \u2018Icing on the cake\u2019 | first = Jacquinn | last = Williams | newspaper = Bay State Banner }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=bba>{{cite web| url = https://bostonbar.org/membership/events/event-details?ID=3296 | title = A Tribute to Judge Judith Nelson Dilday and Probation Officer Joseph O'Connor | accessdate = April 3, 2020 | publisher = Boston Bar Association }}</ref>\n\n<Ref name=martindale>{{Cite web | url = https://www.martindale.com/attorney/judith-nelson-dilday-666237/ | title = Judith Nelson Dilday | accessdate = April 3, 2020 | publisher = Martindale-Hubbell }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=probate>{{Cite news | url = https://masslawyersweekly.com/2011/05/18/probate-court-gets-new-judge-2/ | title = Probate Court gets new judge | first = Phillip |last =  Bantz | date = May 18, 2011 | accessdate = April 3, 2020 | newspaper = Massachusetts Lawyer's Weekly }}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Smith2012\">{{cite book|last=Smith|first=Jessie Carney |title=Black Firsts: 4,000 Ground-Breaking and Pioneering Historical Events|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=steLXpuOONEC&pg=PT593|accessdate=April 3, 2020|date=December 1, 2012|publisher=Visible Ink Press|isbn=978-1-57859-425-2|page=593}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dilday, Judith Nelson}}\n\n[[Category:African-American judges]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts state court judges]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Pittsburgh]]\n[[Category:Educators from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Millersville State College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "NOLA1982", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegal career:fix typo in wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Judith_Nelson_Dilday"}
{"title_page": "Mandr\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Mandr\u00e9\n|Alias            = Andre Lewis<br />The Masked Marauder<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mandr%C3%A9-mn0001448488/biography|title=Mandr\u00e9 - Biography & History - AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_name      = Michael Andre Lewis\n|birth_date      = December 7, 1948\n|death_date      = January 31, 2012<br />[[Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]\n|image           = \n|caption         = \n|background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|occupation      = Musician, producer\n|origin          = [[Omaha]], [[Nebraska]]\n|genre           = [[Funk]], [[Rock music|rock]]<br />[[rhythm and blues]], [[blues]]<br />[[electronic music]]\n|instruments     = [[synthesizer]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]]\n|years_active    = 70's - 80's\n|label           = [[Motown Records]]<br />Rush Hour <br />Mirror's Cage Records\n|associated_acts = [[Johnny Guitar Watson]]<br />[[Frank Zappa]]<br />[[Maxayn]]<br />[[Buddy Miles]]\n|website         = \n}}\n\n'''Michael Andre Lewis''', aka '''Mandr\u00e9''', (December 7, 1948 in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] &ndash; January 31, 2012 in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]) was an American musician known for his [[synthesizer]] recordings at [[Motown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waxpoetics.com/features/in-memoriam/andre-lewis|title=Andre Lewis - Wax Poetics|date=26 February 2012|website=Waxpoetics.com|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> As '''Andre Lewis''' he also contributed to [[Labelle]]'s ''[[Moon Shadow (album)|Moon Shadow]]'' and [[Whitney Houston]]'s ''[[Just Whitney]]''. He toured or recorded with [[Grant Green]], [[The Who]], [[Labelle]], [[Buddy Miles|Buddy Miles Band]], [[Maxayn]], [[Rufus]], White Chocolate, [[Earth Wind and Fire]] and [[Frank Zappa]]. He was also band leader for [[Johnny Guitar Watson]].\n\nHis debut single as '''Mandr\u00e9''' \"Solar Flight (Opus I)\", was a hit from a self-titled debut album ''Mandr\u00e9''.<ref>Ben Watson, W. C. Bamberger - Honesty Is Explosive!: Selected Music Journalism 2010- Page 49 \"not since the albums Mandre cut for Motown in the mid-' 70s had black pop been so keyboard-based and hi-tech. This was dance music by someone who understood New Wave starkness and minimalism.\"</ref> He formerly played with his band [[Maxayn]], named after the singer, and later his wife, Maxayn Lewis, (born Paulette Parker).<ref>The Gangster of Love: Johnny Guitar Watson Vincent Bakker - 2009  Page 88 \"In fact, this was an existing band, formed by Emry Thomas and Andre Lewis, called Maxayn. Watson became a member, Andre is still the leader. The band was named after Maxayn Lewis, singing member and then the wife of Andre Lewis, \"</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n*''Mandr\u00e9'' - 1977\n*''Mandr\u00e9 Two'' - 1978\n*''M3000'' - 1979\n*''Mandr\u00e9 4'' - 1982\n*''A Difficult Journey'' - 2008<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Mandr%C3%A9-A-Difficult-Journey/release/6198929</ref>\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Solar Flight (Opus 1)\" 1977\n* \"Keep Tryin'\" 1977\n* Opus III\n* \"Fair Game\" / \"Light Years\" (Opus IV) 1978\n* \"Spirit Groove\" 1979\n* \"Freakin's Fine\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandre}}\n[[Category:American male musicians]]\n[[Category:American musicians]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n\n\n{{US-musician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n|name            = Mandr\u00e9\n|Alias            = Andre Lewis<br />The Masked Marauder<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mandr%C3%A9-mn0001448488/biography|title=Mandr\u00e9 - Biography & History - AllMusic|website=AllMusic|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n|birth_name      = Michael Andre Lewis\n|birth_date      = December 7, 1948\n|death_date      = January 31, 2012<br />[[Shreveport]], [[Louisiana]]\n|image           = \n|caption         = \n|background      = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n|occupation      = Musician, producer\n|origin          = [[Omaha]], [[Nebraska]]\n|genre           = [[Funk]], [[Rock music|rock]]<br />[[rhythm and blues]], [[blues]]<br />[[electronic music]]\n|instruments     = [[synthesizer]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], [[Bass (guitar)|bass]]\n|years_active    = 70's - 80's\n|label           = [[Motown Records]]<br />Rush Hour <br />Mirror's Cage Records\n|associated_acts = [[Johnny Guitar Watson]]<br />[[Frank Zappa]]<br />[[Maxayn]]<br />[[Buddy Miles]]\n|website         = \n}}\n\n'''Michael Andre Lewis''', aka '''Mandr\u00e9''', (December 7, 1948 in [[Omaha, Nebraska]] &ndash; January 31, 2012 in [[Shreveport, Louisiana]]) was an American musician known for his [[synthesizer]] recordings at [[Motown]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.waxpoetics.com/features/in-memoriam/andre-lewis|title=Andre Lewis - Wax Poetics|date=26 February 2012|website=Waxpoetics.com|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> As '''Andre Lewis''' he also contributed to [[Labelle]]'s ''[[Moon Shadow (album)|Moon Shadow]]'' and [[Whitney Houston]]'s ''[[Just Whitney]]''. He toured or recorded with [[Grant Green]], [[The Who]], [[Labelle]], [[Buddy Miles|Buddy Miles Band]], [[Maxayn]], [[Rufus]], White Chocolate, [[Earth Wind and Fire]] and [[Frank Zappa]]. He was also band leader for [[Johnny Guitar Watson]].\n\nHis debut single as '''Mandr\u00e9''' \"Solar Flight (Opus I)\", was a hit from a self-titled debut album ''Mandr\u00e9''.<ref>Ben Watson, W. C. Bamberger - Honesty Is Explosive!: Selected Music Journalism 2010- Page 49 \"not since the albums Mandre cut for Motown in the mid-' 70s had black pop been so keyboard-based and hi-tech. This was dance music by someone who understood New Wave starkness and minimalism.\"</ref> He formerly played with his band [[Maxayn]], named after the singer, and later his wife, Maxayn Lewis, (born Paulette Parker).<ref>The Gangster of Love: Johnny Guitar Watson Vincent Bakker - 2009  Page 88 \"In fact, this was an existing band, formed by Emry Thomas and Andre Lewis, called Maxayn. Watson became a member, Andre is still the leader. The band was named after Maxayn Lewis, singing member and then the wife of Andre Lewis, \"</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Albums===\n*''Mandr\u00e9'' - 1977\n*''Mandr\u00e9 Two'' - 1978\n*''M3000'' - 1979\n*''Mandr\u00e9 4'' - 1982\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Solar Flight (Opus 1)\" 1977\n* \"Keep Tryin'\" 1977\n* Opus III\n* \"Fair Game\" / \"Light Years\" (Opus IV) 1978\n* \"Spirit Groove\" 1979\n* \"Freakin's Fine\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandre}}\n[[Category:American male musicians]]\n[[Category:American musicians]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Omaha, Nebraska]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n\n\n{{US-musician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MichaelStark55", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAlbums", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandr%C3%A9"}
{"title_page": "Roman salute", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n[[File:Jacques-Louis David - Oath of the Horatii - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|300px|''[[Oath of the Horatii|The Oath of the Horatii]]'' (1786), by [[Jacques-Louis David]]]]\n\nThe '''Roman salute''' ([[Italian language|Italian]]: ''saluto romano'') is a [[salute|gesture]] in which the arm is fully extended, facing forward, with palm down and fingers touching. In some versions, the arm is raised upward at an angle; in others, it is held out parallel to the ground. In contemporary times, the former is widely considered a symbol of [[fascism]] that is commonly perceived to be based on a custom in [[ancient Rome]].<ref name=\"Winkler\">Winkler (2009), p. 2</ref> However, no [[Latin literature|Roman text]] gives this description, and the [[Roman art|Roman works of art]] that display salutational gestures bear little resemblance to the modern Roman salute.<ref name=\"Winkler\" />\n\nBeginning with [[Jacques-Louis David]]'s painting ''[[The Oath of the Horatii]]'' (1784), an association of the gesture with Roman republican and imperial culture emerged.  The gesture and its identification with [[Culture of ancient Rome|Roman culture]] were further developed in other [[Neoclassicism|neoclassic artworks]]. This was further elaborated upon in [[popular culture]] during the late 19th and [[Early 20th century|early 20th]] centuries in plays and films that portrayed the salute as an ancient Roman custom. These included a 1914 [[Italy|Italian]] [[Italian cinema|film]] called ''[[Cabiria]]'' whose intertitles were written by the nationalist poet [[Gabriele d'Annunzio]]. In 1919, d'Annunzio adopted the cinematographically depicted salute as a neo-imperial ritual when [[Italian Regency of Carnaro#Impresa di Fiume|he led the occupation of]] [[Fiume]].\n\nThrough d'Annunzio's influence, the gesture soon became part of the rising [[Italian Fascism|Italian Fascist]] movement's symbolic repertoire. In 1923 the salute was gradually adopted by the Italian Fascist regime. It was then adopted and made compulsory within the [[Nazi Party]] in 1926, and gained national prominence in the German state when the Nazis took power in 1933. It was also adopted by other fascist, [[Far-right politics|far right]] and [[Ultranationalism|ultranationalist]] movements.\n\nSince the end of [[World War II]], displaying the [[Nazi salute|Nazi variant of the salute]] has been a [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|criminal offence]] in [[Germany]], [[Austria]], the [[Czech Republic]], [[Slovakia]], and [[Poland]]. Legal restrictions on its use in [[Italy]] are more nuanced and use there has generated controversy.<ref>  Since the historicity of the salute has never been properly questioned, performing it is prosecutable only when \"meant to exalt exponents, principles, events and methods\" of the extinct [[National Fascist Party]].</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 2018-02-20 | title = Saluto fascista, la Cassazione: \"Non \u00e8 reato se commemorativo\" e conferma due assoluzioni a Milano | trans-title = Fascist salute, Supreme Court of Cassation: \"Not a crime if memorial\" and confirms two acquittals in Milan | url = https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2018/02/20/news/saluto_fascista_per_la_cassazione_non_e_reato_se_commemorativo-189320383/ | language = Italian | work = [[La Repubblica]] | location = Milan | access-date = 2020-01-03}}</ref> The gesture and its variations continue to be used in [[neo-fascist]], [[neo-Nazi]], and [[Falangism|Falangist]] contexts.\n\n==Early Roman sources and images==\n[[File:062 Conrad Cichorius, Die Reliefs der Traianss\u00e4ule, Tafel LXII.jpg|thumb|[[Column of Trajan|Trajan's Column]], Plate LXII. Onlookers raise their arms to acclaim the emperor]]\nThe modern gesture consists of stiffly extending the right arm frontally and raising it roughly 135 degrees from the body's vertical axis, with the palm of the hand facing down and the fingers stretched out and touching each other.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> According to common perceptions, this salute was based on an ancient Roman custom.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> However, this description is unknown in Roman literature and is never mentioned by ancient historians of Rome.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> Not a single Roman work of art, be it sculpture, coinage, or painting, displays a salute of this kind.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> The gesture of the raised right arm or hand in Roman and other ancient cultures that ''does'' exist in surviving literature and art generally had a significantly different function and is never identical with the modern straight-arm salute.<ref name=\"Winkler\" />\n\nThe right hand (Lat. ''dextera'', ''dextra''; Gr. \u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac - ''dexia'') was commonly used in antiquity as a symbol of pledging trust, friendship or loyalty.<ref>K.E. Georges, ''Ausf\u00fchrliches lateinisch-deutsches Handw\u00f6rterbuch'', Leipzig, Hahn'sche Verlags-buchhandlung Lateinisch-deutscher theil. 1879\u201380. 2 v.--Deutsch-lateinischer theil 1882 2 v (reprint Berlin 2007), s.v. \"dexter\"; cf. ''Lewis-Short'' s.v. \"dextera\"; cf. ''LSJ'' s.v. \"\u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac\".</ref> For example, [[Cicero]]  reported that [[Augustus|Octavian]] pledged an oath to [[Julius Caesar]] while outstretching his right hand: \"Although that youth [the young Caesar Octavian] is powerful and has told [[Mark Antony|Antony]] off nicely: yet, after all, we must wait to see the end.\" But what a speech! He swore his oath with the words: \"so may I achieve the honours of my father!\", and at the same time he stretched out his right hand in the direction of his statue.<ref>It is unknown if Octavian's specific oath salute was a pre-existing Roman custom or if he modified a similar pledging gesture for his ''contio'', but Cicero clearly disapproved of Octavian's performance, exclaiming: \"I don't want to be saved by such a man\"; cf. Cic. ''Att.'' [http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/att16.shtml#15 16.15.3.6]: ''Quamquam enim \u2020postea\u2020 in praesentia belle iste puer retundit Antonium, tamen exitum exspectare debemus. at quae contio! nam est missa mihi. iurat \"ita sibi parentis honores consequi liceat\" et simul dextram intendit ad statuam. \u03bc\u03b7\u03b4\u1f72 \u03c3\u03c9\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03b7\u03bd \u1f50\u03c0\u03cc \u03b3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5! [Nec servatoribus istis!]''</ref>\n\n[[File:Statue-Augustus.jpg|thumb|[[Augustus of Prima Porta]]]]Sculptures commemorating military victories such as those on the [[Arch of Titus]], the [[Arch of Constantine]], or on the [[Column of Trajan]] are the best known examples of raised arms in art from this period.<ref name=\"Winkler17\">Winkler (2009), pp. 17</ref>  However these monuments do not display a single clear image of the Roman salute.<ref name=\"Winkler17\" />\n\nThe images closest in appearance to a raised arm salute are scenes in Roman sculpture and coins which show an ''[[adlocutio]]'', ''[[acclamatio]]'', ''[[Adventus (ceremony)|adventus]]'', or ''[[profectio]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler20\" >Winkler (2009), p. 20</ref> These are occasions when a high-ranking official, such as a general or the Emperor, addresses individuals or a group, often soldiers. Unlike modern custom, in which both the leader and the people he addresses raise their arms, most of these scenes show only the senior official raising his hand.<ref name=\"Winkler2021\">Winkler (2009), pp. 20\u201321</ref> Occasionally it is a sign of [[greeting]] or benevolence, but usually it is used as an indication of power.<ref name=\"Winkler2021\" /> An opposite depiction is the ''salutatio'' of a ''diogmites'', a military police officer, who raises his right arm to greet his commander during his ''adventus'' on a relief from 2nd-century [[Ephesus]].<ref>Probably as an ''acclamatio''; note palm is perpendicular to the ground and thumb is sticking up cf. Graham Sumner, ''Roman military clothing: 100 BC \u2013 AD 200'', Oxford 2002, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Co4IB3zPAmYC&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q=&f=false p. 47], pl. G3 (''Diogmitoi'' [sic! correct plural: ''diogmitai'']).</ref>\n\nAn example of a salutational gesture of imperial power can be seen in the statue of [[Augustus of Prima Porta]] which follows certain guidelines set out by oratory scholars of his day.<ref name=\"Moon\" /> In ''[[Rhetorica ad Herennium]]'' the anonymous author states that the orator \"will control himself in the entire frame of his body and in the manly angle of his flanks, with the extension of the arm in the impassioned moments of speech, and by drawing in the arm in relaxed moods\".<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite book|last=Moon|first=Warren G.|title=Polykleitos, the Doryphoros, and tradition|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|year=1995|edition=illustrated|series=Wisconsin studies in classics|pages=271\u2013272|isbn=978-0-299-14310-7}}</ref> [[Quintilian]] states in his ''Institutio Oratoria'': \"Experts do not permit the hand to be raised above the level of the eyes or lowered beneath the breast; to such a degree is this true that it is considered a fault to direct the hand above the head or lower it to the lower part of the belly. It may be extended to the left within the limits of the shoulder, but beyond that it is not fitting.\"<ref name=\"Moon\" />\n\n==18th\u201319th centuries France==\n[[File:Le Serment du Jeu de paume.jpg|thumb|''[[The Tennis Court Oath]]'' (1791), by J-L David]]\n[[File:Jacques Louis David-Serment de l'arm\u00e9e fait \u00e0 l'Empereur apr\u00e8s la distribution des aigles, 5 d\u00e9cembre 1804.jpg|thumb|''[[The Distribution of the Eagle Standards]]'']]\n\nBeginning with [[Jacques-Louis David]]'s painting ''[[The Oath of the Horatii]]'' (1784), an association of the gesture with Roman republican and imperial culture emerged.<ref name=\"Winkler55\">Winkler (2009), p. 55 ''The raised arm, first stretched out as a symbol of righteous fervor-as the Horatii evince it-and later as a symbol of political allegiance and religious-political unity between a people and its leader, becomes an important part of the iconography of new societies. In addition to its specific contemporary use the gesture comes to express, in a fashion that appears timeless and even mystical, an appeal to a higher being and to a heroic ancient past that had served as a model for most of Western civilization for centuries, although often in ways not supported by historical fact. David\u2019s Oath of the Horatii provided the starting point for an arresting gesture that progressed from oath-taking to what will become known as the Roman salute.''</ref><ref name=\"Boime87\">{{cite book|last=Boime|first=Albert|title=Art in an age of revolution, 1750\u20131800|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1987|series=Social history of modern art|volume=Volume 1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/artinageofrevolu00boim/page/400 400\u2013401]|isbn=978-0-226-06334-8|url=https://archive.org/details/artinageofrevolu00boim/page/400}}</ref>  The painting shows the three sons of Horatius swear on their swords, held by their father, that they will defend Rome to the death.<ref name=\"Roth\">{{cite book|last=Roth|first=Michael |title=Rediscovering history: culture, politics, and the psyche|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1994|page=308|chapter=Facing the Patriarch in Early Davidian Painting|isbn=978-0-8047-2313-8}}</ref> It is based on a historical event described by [[Livy]] (Book I, sections 24-6) and elaborated by [[Dionysius of Halicarnassus|Dionysius]] in ''Roman Antiquities'' (Book III).<ref name=\"Marvin\">{{cite book|last=Marvin|first=Roberta Montemorra |author2=Downing A. Thomas |title=Operatic migrations: transforming works and crossing boundaries|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2006|edition=illustrated|pages=102\u2013103|chapter=Roman Republicanism and Operatic Heroines|isbn=978-0-7546-5098-0}}</ref> However, the moment depicted in David's painting is his own creation.<ref name=\"Winkler44\">Winkler (2009), p. 44</ref> Neither Livy nor Dionysius mention any oath taking episode.<ref name=\"Roth\" /> Dionysius, the more detailed source, reports that the father had left to his sons the decision to fight then raised his hands to the heavens to thank the gods.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" />\n\nDominating the center of ''The Oath of the Horatii'' is the brothers' father, facing left. He has both hands raised.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" /> His left hand is holding three swords, while his right hand is empty, with fingers stretched but not touching.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" /> The brother closest to the viewer is holding his arm almost horizontally.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" />  The brother on the left is holding his arm slightly higher, while the third brother holds his hand higher still.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" /> While the first brother extends his right arm, the other two are extending their ''left'' arms. The succession of arms raised progressively higher leads to a gesture closely approximating the style used by fascists in the 20th century in Italy, albeit with the \"wrong\" arms.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" />\n\nArt historian [[Albert Boime]] provides the following analysis:\n\n{{quote|The brothers stretch out their arms in a salute that has since become associated with tyranny. The \"Hail Caesar\" of antiquity (although at the time of the Horatii a Caesar had yet to be born) was transformed into the \"Heil Hitler\" of the modern period. The fraternal intimacy brought about by the Horatii's dedication to absolute principles of victory or death&nbsp;... is closely related to the establishment of the fraternal order&nbsp;... In the total commitment or blind obedience of a single, exclusive group lies the potentiality of the authoritarian state.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />}}\n\nAfter the [[French Revolution]] of 1789, David was commissioned to depict the formation of the revolutionary government in a similar style. In the ''[[Tennis Court Oath]]'' (1792) the [[National Assembly (French Revolution)|National Assembly]] are all depicted with their arms outstretched, united in an upward gesture comparable to that of the Horatii, as they swear to create a new constitution.<ref>Parker (1990), p. 87</ref> The painting was never finished, but an immense drawing was exhibited in 1791 alongside the ''Oath of the Horatii''.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />  As in the ''Oath of the Horatii'', David conveys the unity of minds and bodies in the service of the patriotic ideal.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />  But in this drawing, he takes the subject further, uniting the people beyond just family ties and across different classes, religions, and philosophical opinions.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />\n\n[[File:Ave Caesar Morituri te Salutant (G\u00e9r\u00f4me) 01.jpg|thumb|''Ave Caesar Morituri te Salutant'', by [[Jean-L\u00e9on G\u00e9r\u00f4me]] (1859)]]After the [[First French Republic|republican government]] was replaced by [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]]'s [[First French Empire|imperial r\u00e9gime]], David further deployed the gesture in ''[[The Distribution of the Eagle Standards]]'' (1810).<ref name=\"Winkler51\">Winkler (2009), p. 51</ref>  But unlike his previous paintings representing republican ideals, in ''Eagle Standards'' the oath of allegiance is pledged to a central authority figure, and in imperial fashion.<ref name=\"Winkler51\" /> Boime sees the series of oath pictures as \"the coding of key developments in the history of the Revolution and its culmination in Napoleonic authoritarianism\".<ref name=\"Boime93\">{{cite book|last=Boime|first=Albert |title=Art in an age of Bonapartism, 1800\u20131815 |publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1993|edition=reprint, illustrated|series=Social history of modern art|volume=2|page=46}}</ref>\n\nThe imperial oath is seen in other paintings, such as [[Jean-L\u00e9on G\u00e9r\u00f4me]]'s ''[[Ave Caesar morituri te salutant|Ave Caesar! Morituri te salutant]] (Hail, Caesar, those who are about to die salute you)'' of 1859.<ref name=\"Winkler40\">Winkler (2009), p. 40</ref>  In this painting, the [[gladiators]] are all raising their right or left arms, holding [[tridents]] and other weapons.<ref name=\"Winkler40\" />  Their salutation is a well-known [[Latin phrase]] quoted in [[Suetonius]], ''[[De Vita Caesarum]]'' (\"The Life of the Caesars\", or \"The Twelve Caesars\").<ref>[[Suetonius]], ''[[De Vita Caesarum]]: Divus Claudius'', 21.6</ref> Despite becoming widely popularised in later times, the phrase is unknown in Roman history aside from this isolated use, and it is questionable whether it was ever a customary salute, as is often believed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Baker|first=Alan|title=The gladiator: the secret history of Rome's warrior slaves|publisher=Ebury Press|year=2000|page=84|isbn=978-0-09-187880-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=20YTAQAAIAAJ&q=%22morituri+te+salutant%22+Claudius&dq=%22morituri+te+salutant%22+Claudius&cd=7}}</ref> It was more likely to be an isolated appeal by desperate captives and criminals condemned to die.<ref name=\"kyle\">{{cite book|last=Kyle|first=Donald|title=Spectacles of death in ancient Rome  |publisher=Routledge|year=2001|page=94|isbn=978-0-415-24842-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1GYH63-fARUC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=%22morituri+te+salutant%22+commodus&q=%22morituri%20te%20salutant%22%20commodus}}</ref>\n\n==19th\u201320th centuries United States==\n[[File:Students pledging allegiance to the American flag with the Bellamy salute.jpg|thumb|left|Children performing the [[Bellamy salute]] to the [[flag of the United States]]]]\nOn October 12, 1892, the [[Bellamy salute]] was demonstrated as the [[salute|hand gesture]] to accompany the [[Pledge of Allegiance (United States)|Pledge of Allegiance]] in the United States. The inventor of the saluting gesture was James B. Upham, junior partner and editor of ''The Youth's Companion''.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Margarette S.|title=Twenty Three Words: A Biography of Francis Bellamy: Author of the Pledge of Allegiance|publisher=Natl Bellamy Award|year=1976|isbn=978-0-686-15626-0}}</ref>  Bellamy recalled Upham, upon reading the pledge, came into the posture of the salute, snapped his heels together, and said \"Now up there is the flag; I come to salute; as I say 'I pledge allegiance to my flag,' I stretch out my right hand and keep it raised while I say the stirring words that follow.\"<ref name=\"Miller\" />\n\nAs fascism took hold in Europe, controversy grew on the use of the Bellamy salute given its similarity to the Roman Salute.  When war broke out in 1939, the controversy intensified. School boards around the country revised the salute to avoid the similarity. There was a counter-backlash from the United States Flag Association and the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]], who felt it inappropriate for Americans to have to change the traditional salute because aliens had later adopted a similar gesture.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ellis |first1=Richard |title=To the Flag: The Unlikely History of the Pledge of Allegiance |date=2005 |publisher=University Press of Kansas |pages=113\u2013116 |edition=illustrated}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 1942, at the urging of the [[American Legion]] and the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]], Congress passed [[s: Public Law 77-623|Public Law 77-623]], which codified the etiquette used to display and pledge allegiance to the flag.  This included use of the Bellamy salute, specifically that the pledge \"be rendered by standing with the right hand over the heart; extending the right hand, palm upward, toward the flag at the words \u2018\u2018to the flag\u2019\u2019 and holding this position until the end, when the hand drops to the side.\"  Congress did not discuss or take into account the controversy over use of the salute. Congress later amended the code on December 22, 1942 when it passed [[s: Public Law 77-623|Public Law 77-829]].  Among other changes, it eliminated the Bellamy salute and replaced it with the stipulation that the pledge  \"be rendered by standing with the right hand over the heart.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ellis |first1=Richard |title=To the Flag: The Unlikely History of the Pledge of Allegiance |date=2005 |publisher=University Press of Kansas |pages=116\u2013118 |edition=illustrated}}</ref>\n\n==Early 20th century in theatre and film==\nThe gesture, already established in the United States through the Bellamy salute, has been traced to the [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] production of the play ''[[Ben-Hur (play)|Ben-Hur]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler70\">Winkler (2009), p. 70</ref>  The play, based on [[Lew Wallace]]'s book ''[[Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ]]'', opened on Broadway in November 1899 and proved to be a great success.<ref name=\"Winkler71\">Winkler (2009), p. 71</ref>  Photographs show several scenes using the gesture, including one of Ben-Hur greeting a seated sheik and another of a small crowd so greeting Ben-Hur in his chariot.<ref name=\"Winkler73\">Winkler (2009), p. 73</ref>  Neither Wallace's novel nor text for the theatrical production mentions a raised arm salute.<ref name=\"Winkler73\" />  The salute was evidently added in keeping with the exaggerated style of acting in 19th century theater, which in turn influenced acting in the silent cinema.<ref name=\"Winkler75\">Winkler (2009), p. 75</ref>\n\nThe salute frequently occurs in early 20th century films set in antiquity, such as the American [[Ben-Hur (1907)|''Ben-Hur'' (1907)]] and the Italian ''[[Nerone (film)|Nerone]]'' (1908), although such films do not yet standardize it or make it exclusively Roman.<ref name=\"APA\" /> In ''Spartaco'' (1914), even the slave [[Spartacus]] uses it.<ref name=\"APA\" /> Later examples appear in ''[[Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ (1925 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1925) and in Cecil B. DeMille's ''[[The Sign of the Cross (1932 film)|Sign of the Cross]]'' (1932) and ''[[Cleopatra (1934 film)|Cleopatra]]'' (1934), although the execution of the gesture is still variable.<ref name=\"APA\">{{cite journal|last=Winkler|first=Martin|title=The Roman Salute on Film|journal=2003 APA Annual Meeting |publisher=The American Philological Association (APA)|issue=January 8, 2003|url=http://www.apaclassics.org/AnnualMeeting/03mtg/abstracts/Winkler.html}}</ref>\n\nOf special note is the use in [[Giovanni Pastrone]]'s colossal epic ''[[Cabiria]]'' (1914).<ref name=\"Winkler9495\">Winkler (2009), pp. 94\u201395</ref>  It's intertitles, character names, and movie title was attributed to Italian nationalist [[Gabriele d'Annunzio]], who was known as the \"poet-warrior\".<ref>Leeden (2001), p. 67</ref>  Inspired by the [[Italo-Turkish War]], in which Italy conquered the North African [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] province of [[Tripolitania]], Pastrone perused a politically volatile issue.<ref name=\"Solomon\">{{cite book|last=Solomon|first=Jon|title=The ancient world in the cinema|url=https://archive.org/details/ancientworldinci00solo|url-access=registration|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2001|edition=2, revised, illustrated|page=[https://archive.org/details/ancientworldinci00solo/page/48 48]|isbn=978-0-300-08337-8}}</ref> The film highlights Italy's Roman past and the \"monstrous\" nature of [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] society, which is contrasted with the \"nobility\" of Roman society.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wood|first=Mary P.|title=Italian cinema|publisher=Berg Publishers|year=2005|page=138|isbn=978-1-84520-162-3}}</ref> ''Cabiria'' was one of several films of the period that \"helped resuscitate a distant history that legitimized Italy's past and inspired its dreams\" and which \"delivered the spirit for conquest that seemed to arrive from the distant past\", thereby presaging the \"political rituals of fascism\", \"thanks&nbsp;... to its prime supporter and apostle, Gabriele d'Annunzio.\"<ref name=\"Brunetta\">{{cite book|last=Brunetta|first=Gian Piero |author2=Jeremy Parzen |title=The History of Italian Cinema: A Guide to Italian Film from Its Origins to the Twenty-First Century|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2009|page=34|isbn=978-0-691-11988-5}}</ref>\n\nVariations on the salute occur throughout ''Cabiria'' on the part of Romans and Africans.<ref name=\"Winkler99\">Winkler (2009), p. 99</ref>  Scipio uses the gesture once.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  Fulvius Axilla, the story's fictitious hero, twice employs it as a farewell greeting to his hosts.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  The [[Numidian]] king [[Massinissa]], guest of the Carthaginian Hasdrubal, raises his right hand and is so greeted in return, once by the strongman [[Maciste]].<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  Princess [[Sophonisba]] and King [[Syphax]] mutually greet each other by raising their hands and declining their bodies.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  The diversity of the gesture and the variety of nationalities who use it in ''Cabria'' is seen as further evidence that the salute is a modern invention, used in the film to highlight the exotic nature of antiquity.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />\n\n==Adoption during the 20th century==\n\n=== Italy ===\n[[File:Hitlermusso2 edit.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Benito Mussolini]] and Hitler, Mussolini giving the Roman salute, 25 October 1936]]\nD'Annunzio, who had written the subtitles for the silent movie epic [[Cabiria]], appropriated the salute when he occupied [[Fiume]] in 1919.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\">Falasca-Zamponi (2000), p. 110</ref>  D'Annunzio has been described as the [[John the Baptist]] of [[Italian Fascism]],<ref name=\"Leeden\">Leeden (2001), p. xiii</ref> as virtually the entire ritual of Fascism was invented by D'Annunzio during his occupation of Fiume and his leadership of the \"[[Italian Regency of Carnaro]]\".<ref name=\"Paxton\">{{cite book|last=Paxton|first=Robert O.|title=The Anatomy of Fascism|publisher=Random House, Inc.|year=2005|edition=reprint|series=Vintage Series|pages=[https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism0000paxt/page/59 59\u201360]|chapter=Taking Root|isbn=978-1-4000-3391-1|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism0000paxt/page/59}}</ref>  Besides the Roman salute, these included the balcony address, the cries of ''\"[[Alala|Eia, eia, eia! Alal\u00e0]]!\"'', the dramatic and rhetorical dialogues with the crowd, and the use of religious symbols in new secular settings.<ref name=\"Leeden\" />\n\nLike other neo-Imperial rituals utilized by D'Annunzio, the salute became part of the [[Italian Fascism|Italian fascist]] movement's symbolic repertoire.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />  On January 31, 1923, the Ministry of Education instituted a ritual honoring the flag in schools using the Roman salute.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />  In 1925, as Mussolini began his fascitization of the state, the salute was gradually adopted by the regime, and by December 1, 1925 all state civil administrators were required to use it.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />\n\n[[Achille Starace]], the Italian [[National Fascist Party|Fascist Party]] secretary, pushed for measures to make the use of the Roman salute generally compulsory, denouncing [[handshake|hand shaking]] as [[bourgeois]]. He further extolled the salute as \"more hygienic, more aesthetic, and shorter.\" He also suggested that the Roman salute did not imply the necessity of taking off the hat unless one was indoors. By 1932, the salute was adopted as the substitute for the handshake.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />  On August 19, 1933 the military was ordered to use the salute whenever an unarmed detachment of soldiers was called on to render military honors for the King or Mussolini.<ref name=\"NYTaug20\">{{cite news|url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F10B1EFB3E5B137A93C2AB1783D85F478385F9|title=Fascist Salute Is Adopted By Italian Armed Forces|last=Wireless|date=August 20, 1933|work=The New York Times|page=Page 1|accessdate=March 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe symbolic value of the gesture grew, and it was felt that the proper salute \"had the effect of showing the fascist man's decisive spirit, which was close to that of ancient Rome\".<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110111\">Falasca-Zamponi (2000), pp. 110\u2013111</ref> The salute was seen to demonstrate the fascist's \"decisive spirit, firmness, seriousness, and acknowledgment and acceptance of the regime's hierarchical structure\".<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi112113\">Falasca-Zamponi (2000), pp. 112\u2013113</ref>  It was further felt that the correct physical gesture brought forth a change in character.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi113\">Falasca-Zamponi110 (2000), pp. 113</ref> A joke claimed, however, that the Fascist salute used one hand because Italians were tired of raising both hands to surrender during [[World War I]].<ref name=\"gunther1936\">{{cite book | url=https://openlibrary.org/works/OL16059565W/Inside_Europe | title=Inside Europe | publisher=Harper & Brothers | author=Gunther, John | year=1936 | pages=183}}</ref>\n\nThe bourgeois gesture was supposed to disappear from the view of Italians and not contaminate their daily life. In 1938, the party abolished handshaking in films and theater, and on November 21, 1938 the [[Ministry of Popular Culture]] issued orders banning the publishing of photographs showing people shaking hands. Even official photographs of visiting dignitaries were [[Photo manipulation|retouched]] to remove the image of their handshaking.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi113\" />\n\n=== Germany ===\n{{Main|Nazi salute}}\nIn Germany, the salute, sporadically used by the [[Nazi Party]] (NSDAP) since 1923, was made compulsory within the movement in 1926.<ref name=\"Myth26\">Kershaw (2001), p. 26</ref> Called the [[Hitler]] salute (''Hitlergru\u00df''), it functioned both as an expression of commitment within the party and as a demonstrative statement to the outside world.<ref name=\"Tilman\">Tilman (2009), p. 55</ref>  Yet in spite of this demand for the outward display of obedience, the drive to gain acceptance did not go unchallenged, even within the movement.<ref name=\"Tilman\" /> Early objections focused on its resemblance to the Roman salute employed by Fascist Italy, and hence on it not being [[German folklore|Germanic]].<ref name=\"Tilman\" />  In response, efforts were made to establish its pedigree and invent a proper tradition after the fact.<ref name=\"Tilman\" />\n\nThe compulsory use of the Hitler salute for all public employees followed a directive issued by Reich [[Minister of the Interior]] [[Wilhelm Frick]] on July 13, 1933, one day before the ban on all non-Nazi parties.<ref name=\"Myth60\" >Kershaw (2001), p. 60</ref> The [[Wehrmacht]] refused to adopt the Hitler salute and was able for a time to maintain its own customs.<ref name=\"Tilman80\">Tilman (2009), pp. 80\u201382</ref>  The military were required to use the Hitler salute only while singing the [[Horst Wessel Lied]] and [[Deutschlandlied|German national anthem]], and in non-military encounters such as greeting members of the civilian government.<ref name=\"Tilman80\" />  Only after the [[July 20 Plot]] in 1944 were the military forces of the Third Reich ordered to replace the standard military salute with the Hitler salute.<ref name=\"Tilman82\">Tilman (2009), p. 82</ref>\n\n=== Elsewhere ===\n[[File:Metaxas-regime-greek-fascism.png|left|thumb|Salute in the [[Hellenic Parliament|Greek Parliament]], 1938]]\n[[File:Estonian League of Freedom Fighters - Vaps Movement - Roman salute 1.jpg|thumb|Estonian [[Vaps Movement]], 1933]]\n\nSimilar forms of salutes were adopted by various groups. Its use in France dates back to 1925, when the ''[[Jeunesses Patriotes]] (Patriotic Youth)'', a movement led by [[Pierre Taittinger]], would give the fascist salute at meetings while shouting \"Dictatorship!\".<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 40</ref> [[Marcel Bucard]]'s ''[[Mouvement Franciste]],'' founded in September 1933, adopted the salute as well as donning blue shirts and blue berets.<ref>Soucy (1997), p.&nbsp;38\u201339</ref>  ''[[Solidarit\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise]]'' used the salute as well, though its leaders denied the movement was fascist.<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 71</ref>  By 1937, rivalry amongst French right wing parties sometimes caused confusion over salutes.<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 142</ref>  The [[Parti Populaire Fran\u00e7ais]], generally regarded as the most pro-Nazi of France's [[Collaborationism|collaborationist]] parties, adopted a variant of the salute that distinguished itself from others by slightly bending the hand and holding it at face level.<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 217</ref>\n\n[[File:SaudacaoIntegralista1935.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Brazilian Integralism|Integralists]] in [[Brazil]], 1935]]\nIn the early 1930s, the salute was used by members of the [[Estonia]]n nationalist right wing [[Vaps Movement]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U3L6H8eOIb0C&pg=PA1&dq=vaps+movement+nationalist#v=onepage&q=salute&f=false |title=The Radical Right in Interwar Estonia - Andres Kasekamp - Google Boeken |accessdate=2012-09-21|isbn=9780312225988 |last1=Kasekamp |first1=Andres |date=June 3, 2000 }}</ref> as well as the [[Brazilian Integralist Action]], who used to salute by raising one arm. The Brazilian form of the Salute was called \"Anau\u00ea\" \u2013 a word used as a salutation and as a cry by the Brazilian indigenous [[Tupi people|Tupi]] people, meaning \"you are my brother\".<ref name=\"Payne\">{{cite book|last=Payne|first=Stanley |title=A history of fascism, 1914\u20131945 |publisher=Routledge|year=1995|edition=2|page=345|chapter=Fascism outside Europe?|isbn=978-1-85728-595-6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ante Pavelic Parlament.jpg|left|thumb|[[Ante Paveli\u0107]] greeting the [[Croatian parliament]] in February 1943]]\nIn [[Greece]] in 1936, when [[Ioannis Metaxas]] and his [[4th of August Regime]] took power, an almost identical salute was adopted \u2013 first by the [[National Youth Organisation (Greece)|National Youth Organization]] and later by the government as well as common people \u2013 and used even while fighting against Italy and Germany in WW2.\n\n[[File:Francoist demonstration in Salamanca.jpg|thumb|[[Francoist Spain|Francoist]] demonstration in [[Salamanca]], [[Spain]]]]\nIn Spain, on April 27, 1937, General [[Francisco Franco]] formally approved the salute in a decree which made it the official salutation to be used by all except the military, who would continue to use the traditional military salutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Iy8rAAAAIBAJ&pg=2530,3492234&dq|title=Fascist Salute Adopted|date= April 27, 1937|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|page=10|accessdate=February 14, 2010}}</ref> This was repealed in September 1945.<ref>Decreto de la Presidencia del Consejo de Ministros derogando la obligatoriedad del saludo brazo en alto, de fecha 11 de septiembre de 1945, publicado en el B.O.E. n\u00fam, 257 con fecha 14 de septiembre de 1945.</ref>  When the Franco regime restored \"[[Marcha Real]]\" as the Spanish national anthem in 1942 and established unofficial [[Marcha Real#Franco lyrics|new lyrics]] for it, the first stanza referred to the fascist salute:  \"Alzad los brazos, hijos del pueblo espa\u00f1ol\" (\"Raise your arms, sons of the Spanish people\").  These lyrics remained part of the Spanish national anthem until 1978.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elkington |first=Mark |title=Divisive national anthem lyrics ditched |agency=Reuters |date=January 16, 2008 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUSN1610811820080116 |accessdate=2016-08-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter a meeting with Mussolini, in December 1937, [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] Prime Minister [[Milan Stojadinovi\u0107]] and chairman of [[Yugoslav Radical Union]] adopted a version of the salute as he took to styling himself as ''Vo\u0111a (Leader)''.<ref name=\"Bernard\">{{cite book|last=Singleton|first=Frederick Bernard|title=A short history of the Yugoslav peoples|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1985|edition=2, illustrated|page=167|chapter=The kingdom of Yugoslavia|isbn=978-0-521-27485-2}}</ref><ref name=\"Benson\">{{cite book|last=Benson|first=Leslie|title=Yugoslavia: a concise history|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2001|edition=illustrated|page=[https://archive.org/details/yugoslaviaconcis0000bens_i0i2/page/65 65]|chapter=Destruction of the First Yugoslavia|isbn=978-0-333-79241-4|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/yugoslaviaconcis0000bens_i0i2/page/65}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 1939, the salute by raising one arm was adopted in Romania under a statute promulgating the [[National Renaissance Front]].<ref name=\"Routledge\">{{cite book|last=Webb|first=Adrian|title=The Routledge companion to Central and Eastern Europe since 1919|publisher=Routledge|year=2008|series=Routledge companions to history|page=153|chapter=The Rise of Authoritianism 1919\u20131939|isbn=978-0-203-92817-2}}</ref> In Slovakia, the [[Hlinka Guard]]'s ''[[Na str\u00e1\u017e]]!'' (On guard!) consisted of a half-hearted compromise between a friendly wave and a salute with a straight raised arm.<ref name=\"Jelinek\">{{cite journal|last=Jelinek|first=Yeshayahu |year=1971|title=Storm-Troopers in Slovakia: The Rodobrana and the Hlinka Guard |journal=Journal of Contemporary History|publisher=Sage Publications|volume=6|issue=3|page=104|issn=0022-0094|oclc=49976309|jstor=259881|doi=10.1177/002200947100600307}}</ref>\n\n==Post World War II==\n\n===Italy===\nThe salute has been used many times by prominent individuals as well as groups of people since the war. Famed poet [[Ezra Pound]] used the salute in praise of his adopted country of Italy when he returned in 1958 after being released from an insane asylum in America.<ref name=\"NYT58\">{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FA0E12FF3C5F117B93C2A8178CD85F4C8585F9 |title=Pound, in Italy, Gives Fascist Salute; Calls United States an 'Insane Asylum' |date=July 10, 1958 |work=The New York Times |page=56 |accessdate=March 1, 2010}}</ref> The salute was on display in the 1968 funeral for Mussolini's youngest daughter, Anna Maria Mussolini Negri.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F10613F6345D147493C5AB178FD85F4C8685F9 |title=Mussolini's Followers Mourn Death of His Daughter|date=April 27, 1968|work=The New York Times |page=8 |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>  When the [[Italian Social Movement]] had its greatest electoral gains since the Second World War in June, 1971, crowds at the party headquarters cheered and gave the outstretched arm salute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=A5kuAAAAIBAJ&pg=827,3985511 |title=Fascists Make Gains In Italian Elections |last=UPI |date= June 16, 1971 |publisher=Montreal Gazette |page=5 |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> On July 29, 1983, on the 100th anniversary of Mussolini's birth, thousands of black-shirted supporters chanted \"Duce! Duce!\" with their arms raised in the fascist salute on a march from his native village of [[Predappio]] in [[Romagna]] to the cemetery where he was buried.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SRUyAAAAIBAJ&pg=931,2855714 |title=Thousands Give Fascist Salute At Rally To Honor Mussolini |date=July 30, 1983 |publisher=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> On the eve of [[Silvio Berlusconi]]'s election victory in 1994, young supporters of [[Gianfranco Fini]] made the fascist salute while chanting \"Duce! Duce!\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/31/world/italy-s-neo-fascists-have-they-shed-their-past.html?pagewanted=1 |title=Italy's Neo-Fascists: Have They Shed Their Past?|last=COWELL|first=ALAN |date= March 31, 1994 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Italian [[association football|footballer]] [[Paolo Di Canio]] created controversy by twice using the gesture to salute [[S.S. Lazio]] fans, first in a match against archrivals [[A.S. Roma]] and then against [[A.S. Livorno Calcio]]  (a club inclined to leftist politics).<ref name=\"Kassimeris\">{{cite book |last=Kassimeris |first=Christos |title=European football in black and white: tackling racism in football |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2008 |page=70 |isbn=978-0-7391-1960-0}}</ref> Di Canio received a one match game ban after the second event and was fined 7,000 euros, after which he was quoted as saying \"I will always salute as I did because it gives me a sense of belonging to my people [...] I saluted my people with what for me is a sign of belonging to a group that holds true values, values of civility against the standardisation that this society imposes upon us.\"<ref name=\"Nursey\">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/daily-mirror-the-london-uk/mi_8006/is_20051219/football-ll-di-canio-salute/ai_n40766979/ |title=Football: ll Di Canio new salute row |last=Nursey |first=James |date=December 19, 2005 |publisher=The Daily Mirror; London (UK) |accessdate=February 28, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  His salute featured on unofficial merchandise sold outside [[Stadio Olimpico]] after the ban.<ref name=\"Kassimeris\" />  Di Canio has also expressed admiration for [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4158591.stm |title=Footballer's 'fascist salute' row |last=Duff |first=Mark |date=January 9, 2005 |publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=February 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1506262/Im-a-fascist-not-a-racist-says-Paolo-di-Canio.html |title=I'm a fascist, not a racist, says Paolo di Canio |last=Fenton |first=Ben |date=December 24, 2005 |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=February 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn June, 2009, [[Michela Vittoria Brambilla]], an Italian politician and businesswoman commonly described as a possible successor to [[Silvio Berlusconi]] for leadership of the Italian right, was caught in a controversy over her alleged use of the Roman salute, with calls for her to step down.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8563250|title=Italy official in row over apparent fascist salute|last=AP foreign |date=June 17, 2009 |publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>  She denied the accusation, stating \"I've never either done or thought of doing any gesture that is an apology of fascism, something toward which I've never showed any indulgence, let alone sympathy. And why should I have made a public display of such a despicable gesture shortly after I've been made a minister?\"<ref name=\"Guardian2009\" /> A video of the event was posted on the Web site of the newspaper ''La Repubblica'' that showed Brambilla extending her right arm upward in what appears to be a fascist salute.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\" />  Brambilla said she was just greeting the crowd.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\" />\n\n===Germany===\nUse of the salute and accompanying phrases has been forbidden by law in Germany since the end of World War II. [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|Section 86a]] of the German Penal Code provides for punishment of up to three years in prison for anyone using the salute, unless it is used for artistic, scientific, or educational purposes.<ref name=\"Tilman9495\">Tilman (2009), p.&nbsp;94\u201395</ref>\n\n===Greece===\nThe Greek nationalist party [[Golden Dawn (Greece)|Golden Dawn]] uses the Roman salute unofficially. Golden Dawn is accused by its opponents of being neo-Nazi, but the party denies this and claims that the salute is ancient Greek or Roman, and that it is used as a tribute to [[Ioannis Metaxas]] and his [[4th of August Regime]] which led Greece against the foreign occupation forces in WWII.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madata.gr/epikairotita/politics/230568.html |title=\u039f \u03bd\u03b1\u03b6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03cd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2 |publisher=Madata.GR |date=2008-10-09 |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ethnos.gr/article.asp?catid=22767&subid=2&pubid=63638177 | work=Ethnos | title=\u03a4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a7\u03af\u03c4\u03bb\u03b5\u03c1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \"\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2\" | access-date=March 11, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233050/http://www.ethnos.gr/article.asp?catid=22767&subid=2&pubid=63638177 | archive-date=June 6, 2014 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news |url=http://tvxs.gr/news/ellada/nazistikos-xairetismos-sto-dimotiko-symboylio-tis-lamias-binteo | publisher=tvxs.gr |title=\u039d\u03b1\u03b6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03a3\u03c5\u03bc\u03b2\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039b\u03b1\u03bc\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 |date=11 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tovima.gr/politics/article/?aid=480509 |work=To Vima | title=\u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03bd\u03b1\u03b6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc \u03b7 \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ae \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae |date=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kyriakidou |first=Dina |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/12/us-greece-crisis-dawn-idUSBRE8AB09F20121112 |title=Special Report: Greece's far-right party goes on the offensive |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_12/11/2012_469572 |title=Far-right Golden Dawn goes on the offensive in Greece |publisher=ekathimerini.com |accessdate=2013-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103181611/http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_12/11/2012_469572 |archivedate=January 3, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keeptalkinggreece.com/2012/10/21/golden-dawn-chief-admits-his-party-uses-nazi-salute-and-demonstrates-it-with-a-gesture/ |title=Golden Dawn chief admits his party uses \"nazi salute\" and demonstrates it with a gesture |publisher=Keeptalkinggreece.com |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref>\n\n===The Levant===\nThe salute employed by certain groups and their supporters, like [[Hezbollah]], [[Fatah]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2012/01/26/palestinians-use-nazi-sieg-heil-salute-during-fatah-celebration-in-lebanon/ |title=Theblaze.com |access-date=January 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816142849/https://www.theblaze.com/stories/2012/01/26/palestinians-use-nazi-sieg-heil-salute-during-fatah-celebration-in-lebanon |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> pro-Assad [[National Defence Force (Syria)|NDF]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SKM-Pxh-OUQ YouTube]</ref> and Assad supporters,<ref>[http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/news/syria-loyalists-rally-as-arabs-await-answer-on-deal_3612 Yourmiddleeast.com]</ref> the [[Syrian Social Nationalist Party]], and the [[Kataeb Party]],<ref>[http://www.thearabdigest.com/2012/08/lebanons-phalange-keeps-nazi-salute.html Thearabdigest.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209051913/http://www.thearabdigest.com/2012/08/lebanons-phalange-keeps-nazi-salute.html |date=December 9, 2014 }}</ref> have often been confused with the Roman/Nazi salute, even though in many cases the salute is performed by a closed fist rather than the Roman/Nazi extended palm. Opposition fighters in Syria have also been filmed and documenting using it, or a variance thereof, on multiple occasions.<ref name=\"rocklandtimes.com\">[http://www.rocklandtimes.com/2013/04/05/benghazi-syria-arms-connection/ Rocklandtimes.com]</ref> From its use, a connection between Nazism and these groups is often alleged. Often these allegations are raised at the expense of the opposing groups, pro-Assad sympathizers alleging Nazi sympathies of the Opposition and vice versa.<ref name=\"rocklandtimes.com\"/> However, the oath of allegiance by the Lebanese army, and the salute to the flag uses the Roman salute - possibly influenced by Vichy France shortly before independence was officially gained in 1944 - still continues to be used by the state today.<ref name=\"Lebanese Army oath of allegience\">{{cite web|title=Timeframe 0:06 - 0:07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VBbYBZhbxpU|publisher=Lebanese Army}}</ref>\n\n===Portugal===\nIn Portugal the salute is still used today by the military to take their oath to the national flag, when they successfully complete the first phase of military instruction. Formed in front of the highest symbol of national sovereignty, the military in sense and attunement, raise their right arm pointed towards the flag and take their oath.{{fact|date=October 2019}}\n\n===South Africa===\nThe [[Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging]], a neo-Nazi political party and paramilitary force known for its advocacy of an all-white Afrikaner ''[[Volkstaat]]'',<ref>\"Separation, even after apartheid; Many whites fear for life after [[Nelson Mandela|Mandela]],\" (21 June 2013) ''National Post'', Ontario</ref><ref>\"Extremists Steal Guns for S. Africa War\" (May 30, 1990), ''Elyria Chronicle Telegram''</ref> has utilized Nazi-style uniforms, flags, insignia, and salutes at meetings and public rallies.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QbvzZTB9O0k \"Eugene Terre'Blanche's Afrikaner Resistance Movement - Rally,\" youtube. See 0:40 for salutes.]</ref> Hundreds of supporters in 2010 delivered straight-arm salutes outside the funeral for its founder and former leader [[Eug\u00e8ne Terre'Blanche]], who was murdered by two black farm workers over an alleged wage dispute.<ref>{{Cite web|title=AWB leader Eugene Terreblanche's funeral in Ventersdorp, South Africa, in pictures|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 January 2018|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/7572063/AWB-leader-Eugene-Terreblanches-funeral-in-Ventersdorp-South-Africa-in-pictures.html?image=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=South African white supremacist Eugene Terreblanche laid to rest|publisher=The Telegraph|date=9 April 2010|accessdate=19 January 2018|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/southafrica/7571357/South-African-white-supremacist-Eugene-Terreblanche-laid-to-rest.html}}</ref>\n\n===Red Hand of Ulster Salute===\nThe Red Hand of Ulster Salute is a modified version of the Roman Salute in which the hand is raised vertically to symbolise the [[Red Hand of Ulster]].  It is used by some [[Rangers F.C.]] fans to show an affinity with the [[Ulster loyalism|Loyalist]] cause.  Its similarity to the Nazi salute has caused offence and the [[soccer|football]] club and its supporters' association have asked them not to use it.\n<ref name=BBCSport>\n{{cite web |author= |title=Uefa drops Rangers salute probe|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6383691.stm|publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=21 February 2007}} \n</ref>\n<ref name=HeraldScotland>\n{{cite web |author= |title=Outrage at 'Nazi salutes' by soldiers in front of Union Flag|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13129109.Outrage_at__Nazi_salutes__by_soldiers_in_front_of_Union_Flag/|publisher=[[Herald Scotland]] |date=28 October 2013}} \n</ref>\n\n===Popular culture===\n[[File:11-04-06-LSJUMB-004.jpg|thumb|[[Stanford]] band members doing the Roman salute to the [[Spirit of Troy|marching band]] of rival USC.]]\nA large number of films made after World War II made the Roman salute a visual stereotype of a proto-fascist ancient Roman society.<ref name=\"Winkler151\">Winkler (2009), p. 151</ref>  In the 1951 film ''[[Quo Vadis (1951 film)|Quo Vadis]]'', [[Nero]]'s repeated use of the salute at mass rallies explicitly presents the Roman Empire as a Fascist military state.<ref name=\"Winkler14345\">Winkler (2009), p.&nbsp;143\u2013145</ref>  The movie provided other filmmakers of the time a model,<ref name=\"Winkler151\" /> with notable examples including ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'',<ref name=\"Winkler155\">Winkler (2009), p. 155</ref> ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'',<ref>Winkler (2009), p.158</ref> ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'',<ref>Winkler (2009), p. 159</ref> and ''[[Caligula (film)|Caligula]]''. Not until ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' did the Roman epic return to the cinema.<ref name=\"Winkler164\">Winkler (2009), p. 164</ref>  In this movie, the salute is notably absent in most scenes, for example when [[Commodus]] enters Rome or when the Senate salutes the Emperor by head-bowing.<ref name=\"Winkler164\" />\n\nVariations on the salute also appear in [[neo-fascist]] contexts. For example, The Christian Falangist Party, founded in 1985, uses a \"[[Zogist salute|pectoral salute]]\", in which the right arm, bent at the elbow, is extended from the heart, palm down.<ref>Winkler (2009), p. 6</ref> This gesture was used in [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]]'s [[1966 in film|1966 film]] ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (1966 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler176\">Winkler (2009), p. 176</ref>  The film portrays a futuristic totalitarian society modeled after the fascist state, including black uniforms, [[book burning]]s, and thought control.<ref name=\"Winkler176\" />  In the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' episode \"[[Mirror, Mirror (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Mirror, Mirror]]\", the salute begins with the right fist being placed over the heart, as in a pectoral salute, and then the arm is stretched out (usually up) before the body, open palm down, as in a traditional Roman salute.<ref name=\"Winkler169\">Winkler (2009), p. 169</ref>  In the episode, [[Captain Kirk]] and members of his crew are transported to a parallel universe in which the [[United Federation of Planets]] has been replaced by [[Mirror Universe (Star Trek)|an empire]] characterized by sadistic violence and torture, genocide, and unquestioning obedience to authority.<ref name=\"Winkler169\" /> A modified Roman salute is commonly used in the British-American series ''[[Rome (TV series)|Rome]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler174\">Winkler (2009), p. 174</ref>  Here the salute avoids similarity to the Fascist salute, as the series seeks not to depict these Romans as stereotypical conquerors.<ref name=\"Winkler174\" />  Therefore, the salute is not the familiar straight arm salute but rather resembles a pectoral salute, with the right hand is placed over the heart and then extended to the front of the body.<ref name=\"Winkler174\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin|width=50%}}{{col-break}}\n* [[1968 Olympics Black Power salute]]\n* [[1972 Olympics Black Power salute]]\n* ''[[Ave]]''\n* [[Ave Imperator, morituri te salutant]]\n* [[Bellamy salute]]\n* ''[[Bras d'honneur]]''\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Heil og s\u00e6l]]''\n* [[Olympic_symbols#Olympic_salute|Olympic salute]]\n* [[Quenelle (gesture)]] \n* [[Raised fist]]\n* [[Zogist salute]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Allert|first=Tilman|author2=Translated by Jefferson Chase |title=The Hitler Salute: On the Meaning of a Gesture|publisher=Picador|date=April 2009|edition=Picador|isbn=978-0-312-42830-3}}\n* {{cite book|last=Falasca-Zamponi|first=Simonetta|title=Fascist spectacle: the aesthetics of power in Mussolini's Italy|publisher=University of California Press|year=2000|edition=illustrated|series=Studies on the history of society and culture|volume=28|isbn= 978-0-520-22677-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kershaw|first=Ian|title=The \"Hitler myth\": Image and reality in the Third Reich|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|edition=2, reissue|isbn=978-0-19-280206-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ledeen|first=Michael Arthur|title=D'Annunzio: the first duce|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=2001|edition=2, illustrated|isbn=978-0-7658-0742-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Parker|first=Noel|title=Portrayals of revolution: images, debates, and patterns of thought on the French Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/portrayalsofrevo0000park|url-access=registration|publisher=SIU Press|year=1990|edition=illustrated|isbn=978-0-8093-1684-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Soucy |first=Robert|title=French Fascism: The Second Wave, 1933\u20131939|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1997|edition=illustrated|isbn=978-0-300-07043-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winkler|first=Martin M.|title=The Roman Salute: Cinema, History, Ideology|publisher=Ohio State University Press|location=Columbus|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8142-0864-9}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Roman salutes}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121025144237/http://cache.daylife.com/imageserve/08ZibDD7rV1gS/340x.jpg President of Republic of China (Taiwan) Ma Ying Jeou giving Roman salute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130527141450/http://www.tibet.net/en/flash/2004/0504/images/chen.jpg Former President of Republic of China (Taiwan) Chen Shui Bian giving Roman salute]\n* [http://farm1.static.flickr.com/134/337148966_e51e1d347d.jpg Officials in the Republic of China (Taiwan) being sworn in with Roman Salute]\n* [http://cheiron.humanities.mcmaster.ca/~trajan/images/hi/4.70.h.jpg Photograph] and [https://archive.is/20120524095058/http://cheiron.humanities.mcmaster.ca/~trajan/buildcartoon.cgi?13b \"cartoon view\" explanation] of [[Trajan's Column]], from [[McMaster University]] Humanities department\n*{{cite web|url=http://olympic-museum.de/poster/poster1924.htm |title=Paris 1924 \u2013 Jeux Olympiques |last=Droit |first=Jean |date= |work=From Olympic Games Museum |publisher=French Olympic Committee |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829002316/http://olympic-museum.de/poster/poster1924.htm |archivedate=August 29, 2010 |df= }}. Poster from 1924 Olympics depicting [[Olympic salute]]\n\n{{Fascism}}\n{{Gestures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Salute}}\n[[Category:Ancient Roman society|Salute]]\n[[Category:Greetings]]\n[[Category:Fascist symbols]]\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Gestures of respect]]\n[[Category:Salutes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2011}}\n[[File:Jacques-Louis David - Oath of the Horatii - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|300px|''[[Oath of the Horatii|The Oath of the Horatii]]'' (1786), by [[Jacques-Louis David]]]]\n\nThe '''Roman salute''' ([[Italian language|Italian]]: ''saluto romano'') is a [[salute|gesture]] in which the arm is fully extended, facing forward, with palm down and fingers touching. In some versions, the arm is raised upward at an angle; in others, it is held out parallel to the ground. In contemporary times, the former is widely considered a symbol of [[fascism]] that is commonly perceived to be based on a custom in [[ancient Rome]].<ref name=\"Winkler\">Winkler (2009), p. 2</ref> However, no [[Latin literature|Roman text]] gives this description, and the [[Roman art|Roman works of art]] that display salutational gestures bear little resemblance to the modern Roman salute.<ref name=\"Winkler\" />\n\nBeginning with [[Jacques-Louis David]]'s painting ''[[The Oath of the Horatii]]'' (1784), an association of the gesture with Roman republican and imperial culture emerged.  The gesture and its identification with [[Culture of ancient Rome|Roman culture]] were further developed in other [[Neoclassicism|neoclassic artworks]]. This was further elaborated upon in [[popular culture]] during the late 19th and [[Early 20th century|early 20th]] centuries in plays and films that portrayed the salute as an ancient Roman custom. These included a 1914 [[Italy|Italian]] [[Italian cinema|film]] called ''[[Cabiria]]'' whose intertitles were written by the nationalist poet [[Gabriele d'Annunzio]]. In 1919, d'Annunzio adopted the cinematographically depicted salute as a neo-imperial ritual when [[Italian Regency of Carnaro#Impresa di Fiume|he led the occupation of]] [[Fiume]].\n\nThrough d'Annunzio's influence, the gesture soon became part of the rising [[Italian Fascism|Italian Fascist]] movement's symbolic repertoire. In 1923 the salute was gradually adopted by the Italian Fascist regime. It was then adopted and made compulsory within the [[Nazi Party]] in 1926, and gained national prominence in the German state when the Nazis took power in 1933. It was also adopted by other fascist, [[Far-right politics|far right]] and [[Ultranationalism|ultranationalist]] movements.\n\nSince the end of [[World War II]], displaying the [[Nazi salute|Nazi variant of the salute]] has been a [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|criminal offence]] in [[Germany]], [[Austria]], the [[Czech Republic]], [[Slovakia]], and [[Poland]]. Legal restrictions on its use in [[Italy]] are more nuanced and use there has generated controversy.<ref>  Since the historicity of the salute has never been properly questioned, performing it is prosecutable only when \"meant to exalt exponents, principles, events and methods\" of the extinct [[National Fascist Party]].</ref><ref>{{cite news | date = 2018-02-20 | title = Saluto fascista, la Cassazione: \"Non \u00e8 reato se commemorativo\" e conferma due assoluzioni a Milano | trans-title = Fascist salute, Supreme Court of Cassation: \"Not a crime if memorial\" and confirms two acquittals in Milan | url = https://milano.repubblica.it/cronaca/2018/02/20/news/saluto_fascista_per_la_cassazione_non_e_reato_se_commemorativo-189320383/ | language = Italian | work = [[La Repubblica]] | location = Milan | access-date = 2020-01-03}}</ref> The gesture and its variations continue to be used in [[neo-fascist]], [[neo-Nazi]], and [[Falangism|Falangist]] contexts.\n\n==Early Roman sources and images==\n[[File:062 Conrad Cichorius, Die Reliefs der Traianss\u00e4ule, Tafel LXII.jpg|thumb|[[Column of Trajan|Trajan's Column]], Plate LXII. Onlookers raise their arms to acclaim the emperor]]\nThe modern gesture consists of stiffly extending the right arm frontally and raising it roughly 135 degrees from the body's vertical axis, with the palm of the hand facing down and the fingers stretched out and touching each other.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> According to common perceptions, this salute was based on an ancient Roman custom.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> However, this description is unknown in Roman literature and is never mentioned by ancient historians of Rome.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> Not a single Roman work of art, be it sculpture, coinage, or painting, displays a salute of this kind.<ref name=\"Winkler\" /> The gesture of the raised right arm or hand in Roman and other ancient cultures that ''does'' exist in surviving literature and art generally had a significantly different function and is never identical with the modern straight-arm salute.<ref name=\"Winkler\" />\n\nThe right hand (Lat. ''dextera'', ''dextra''; Gr. \u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac - ''dexia'') was commonly used in antiquity as a symbol of pledging trust, friendship or loyalty.<ref>K.E. Georges, ''Ausf\u00fchrliches lateinisch-deutsches Handw\u00f6rterbuch'', Leipzig, Hahn'sche Verlags-buchhandlung Lateinisch-deutscher theil. 1879\u201380. 2 v.--Deutsch-lateinischer theil 1882 2 v (reprint Berlin 2007), s.v. \"dexter\"; cf. ''Lewis-Short'' s.v. \"dextera\"; cf. ''LSJ'' s.v. \"\u03b4\u03b5\u03be\u03b9\u03ac\".</ref> For example, [[Cicero]]  reported that [[Augustus|Octavian]] pledged an oath to [[Julius Caesar]] while outstretching his right hand: \"Although that youth [the young Caesar Octavian] is powerful and has told [[Mark Antony|Antony]] off nicely: yet, after all, we must wait to see the end.\" But what a speech! He swore his oath with the words: \"so may I achieve the honours of my father!\", and at the same time he stretched out his right hand in the direction of his statue.<ref>It is unknown if Octavian's specific oath salute was a pre-existing Roman custom or if he modified a similar pledging gesture for his ''contio'', but Cicero clearly disapproved of Octavian's performance, exclaiming: \"I don't want to be saved by such a man\"; cf. Cic. ''Att.'' [http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/att16.shtml#15 16.15.3.6]: ''Quamquam enim \u2020postea\u2020 in praesentia belle iste puer retundit Antonium, tamen exitum exspectare debemus. at quae contio! nam est missa mihi. iurat \"ita sibi parentis honores consequi liceat\" et simul dextram intendit ad statuam. \u03bc\u03b7\u03b4\u1f72 \u03c3\u03c9\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03b7\u03bd \u1f50\u03c0\u03cc \u03b3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03b9\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5! [Nec servatoribus istis!]''</ref>\n\n[[File:Statue-Augustus.jpg|thumb|[[Augustus of Prima Porta]]]]Sculptures commemorating military victories such as those on the [[Arch of Titus]], the [[Arch of Constantine]], or on the [[Column of Trajan]] are the best known examples of raised arms in art from this period.<ref name=\"Winkler17\">Winkler (2009), pp. 17</ref>  However these monuments do not display a single clear image of the Roman salute.<ref name=\"Winkler17\" />\n\nThe images closest in appearance to a raised arm salute are scenes in Roman sculpture and coins which show an ''[[adlocutio]]'', ''[[acclamatio]]'', ''[[Adventus (ceremony)|adventus]]'', or ''[[profectio]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler20\" >Winkler (2009), p. 20</ref> These are occasions when a high-ranking official, such as a general or the Emperor, addresses individuals or a group, often soldiers. Unlike modern custom, in which both the leader and the people he addresses raise their arms, most of these scenes show only the senior official raising his hand.<ref name=\"Winkler2021\">Winkler (2009), pp. 20\u201321</ref> Occasionally it is a sign of [[greeting]] or benevolence, but usually it is used as an indication of power.<ref name=\"Winkler2021\" /> An opposite depiction is the ''salutatio'' of a ''diogmites'', a military police officer, who raises his right arm to greet his commander during his ''adventus'' on a relief from 2nd-century [[Ephesus]].<ref>Probably as an ''acclamatio''; note palm is perpendicular to the ground and thumb is sticking up cf. Graham Sumner, ''Roman military clothing: 100 BC \u2013 AD 200'', Oxford 2002, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Co4IB3zPAmYC&pg=PA47#v=onepage&q=&f=false p. 47], pl. G3 (''Diogmitoi'' [sic! correct plural: ''diogmitai'']).</ref>\n\nAn example of a salutational gesture of imperial power can be seen in the statue of [[Augustus of Prima Porta]] which follows certain guidelines set out by oratory scholars of his day.<ref name=\"Moon\" /> In ''[[Rhetorica ad Herennium]]'' the anonymous author states that the orator \"will control himself in the entire frame of his body and in the manly angle of his flanks, with the extension of the arm in the impassioned moments of speech, and by drawing in the arm in relaxed moods\".<ref name=\"Moon\">{{cite book|last=Moon|first=Warren G.|title=Polykleitos, the Doryphoros, and tradition|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|year=1995|edition=illustrated|series=Wisconsin studies in classics|pages=271\u2013272|isbn=978-0-299-14310-7}}</ref> [[Quintilian]] states in his ''Institutio Oratoria'': \"Experts do not permit the hand to be raised above the level of the eyes or lowered beneath the breast; to such a degree is this true that it is considered a fault to direct the hand above the head or lower it to the lower part of the belly. It may be extended to the left within the limits of the shoulder, but beyond that it is not fitting.\"<ref name=\"Moon\" />\n\n==18th\u201319th centuries France==\n[[File:Le Serment du Jeu de paume.jpg|thumb|''[[The Tennis Court Oath]]'' (1791), by J-L David]]\n[[File:Jacques Louis David-Serment de l'arm\u00e9e fait \u00e0 l'Empereur apr\u00e8s la distribution des aigles, 5 d\u00e9cembre 1804.jpg|thumb|''[[The Distribution of the Eagle Standards]]'']]\n\nBeginning with [[Jacques-Louis David]]'s painting ''[[The Oath of the Horatii]]'' (1784), an association of the gesture with Roman republican and imperial culture emerged.<ref name=\"Winkler55\">Winkler (2009), p. 55 ''The raised arm, first stretched out as a symbol of righteous fervor-as the Horatii evince it-and later as a symbol of political allegiance and religious-political unity between a people and its leader, becomes an important part of the iconography of new societies. In addition to its specific contemporary use the gesture comes to express, in a fashion that appears timeless and even mystical, an appeal to a higher being and to a heroic ancient past that had served as a model for most of Western civilization for centuries, although often in ways not supported by historical fact. David\u2019s Oath of the Horatii provided the starting point for an arresting gesture that progressed from oath-taking to what will become known as the Roman salute.''</ref><ref name=\"Boime87\">{{cite book|last=Boime|first=Albert|title=Art in an age of revolution, 1750\u20131800|publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1987|series=Social history of modern art|volume=Volume 1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/artinageofrevolu00boim/page/400 400\u2013401]|isbn=978-0-226-06334-8|url=https://archive.org/details/artinageofrevolu00boim/page/400}}</ref>  The painting shows the three sons of Horatius swear on their swords, held by their father, that they will defend Rome to the death.<ref name=\"Roth\">{{cite book|last=Roth|first=Michael |title=Rediscovering history: culture, politics, and the psyche|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1994|page=308|chapter=Facing the Patriarch in Early Davidian Painting|isbn=978-0-8047-2313-8}}</ref> It is based on a historical event described by [[Livy]] (Book I, sections 24-6) and elaborated by [[Dionysius of Halicarnassus|Dionysius]] in ''Roman Antiquities'' (Book III).<ref name=\"Marvin\">{{cite book|last=Marvin|first=Roberta Montemorra |author2=Downing A. Thomas |title=Operatic migrations: transforming works and crossing boundaries|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|year=2006|edition=illustrated|pages=102\u2013103|chapter=Roman Republicanism and Operatic Heroines|isbn=978-0-7546-5098-0}}</ref> However, the moment depicted in David's painting is his own creation.<ref name=\"Winkler44\">Winkler (2009), p. 44</ref> Neither Livy nor Dionysius mention any oath taking episode.<ref name=\"Roth\" /> Dionysius, the more detailed source, reports that the father had left to his sons the decision to fight then raised his hands to the heavens to thank the gods.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" />\n\nDominating the center of ''The Oath of the Horatii'' is the brothers' father, facing left. He has both hands raised.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" /> His left hand is holding three swords, while his right hand is empty, with fingers stretched but not touching.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" /> The brother closest to the viewer is holding his arm almost horizontally.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" />  The brother on the left is holding his arm slightly higher, while the third brother holds his hand higher still.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" /> While the first brother extends his right arm, the other two are extending their ''left'' arms. The succession of arms raised progressively higher leads to a gesture closely approximating the style used by fascists in the 20th century in Italy, albeit with the \"wrong\" arms.<ref name=\"Winkler44\" />\n\nArt historian [[Albert Boime]] provides the following analysis:\n\n{{quote|The brothers stretch out their arms in a salute that has since become associated with tyranny. The \"Hail Caesar\" of antiquity (although at the time of the Horatii a Caesar had yet to be born) was transformed into the \"Heil Hitler\" of the modern period. The fraternal intimacy brought about by the Horatii's dedication to absolute principles of victory or death&nbsp;... is closely related to the establishment of the fraternal order&nbsp;... In the total commitment or blind obedience of a single, exclusive group lies the potentiality of the authoritarian state.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />}}\n\nAfter the [[French Revolution]] of 1789, David was commissioned to depict the formation of the revolutionary government in a similar style. In the ''[[Tennis Court Oath]]'' (1792) the [[National Assembly (French Revolution)|National Assembly]] are all depicted with their arms outstretched, united in an upward gesture comparable to that of the Horatii, as they swear to create a new constitution.<ref>Parker (1990), p. 87</ref> The painting was never finished, but an immense drawing was exhibited in 1791 alongside the ''Oath of the Horatii''.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />  As in the ''Oath of the Horatii'', David conveys the unity of minds and bodies in the service of the patriotic ideal.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />  But in this drawing, he takes the subject further, uniting the people beyond just family ties and across different classes, religions, and philosophical opinions.<ref name=\"Boime87\" />\n\n[[File:Ave Caesar Morituri te Salutant (G\u00e9r\u00f4me) 01.jpg|thumb|''Ave Caesar Morituri te Salutant'', by [[Jean-L\u00e9on G\u00e9r\u00f4me]] (1859)]]After the [[First French Republic|republican government]] was replaced by [[Napoleon I of France|Napoleon]]'s [[First French Empire|imperial r\u00e9gime]], David further deployed the gesture in ''[[The Distribution of the Eagle Standards]]'' (1810).<ref name=\"Winkler51\">Winkler (2009), p. 51</ref>  But unlike his previous paintings representing republican ideals, in ''Eagle Standards'' the oath of allegiance is pledged to a central authority figure, and in imperial fashion.<ref name=\"Winkler51\" /> Boime sees the series of oath pictures as \"the coding of key developments in the history of the Revolution and its culmination in Napoleonic authoritarianism\".<ref name=\"Boime93\">{{cite book|last=Boime|first=Albert |title=Art in an age of Bonapartism, 1800\u20131815 |publisher=University of Chicago Press|year=1993|edition=reprint, illustrated|series=Social history of modern art|volume=2|page=46}}</ref>\n\nThe imperial oath is seen in other paintings, such as [[Jean-L\u00e9on G\u00e9r\u00f4me]]'s ''[[Ave Caesar morituri te salutant|Ave Caesar! Morituri te salutant]] (Hail, Caesar, those who are about to die salute you)'' of 1859.<ref name=\"Winkler40\">Winkler (2009), p. 40</ref>  In this painting, the [[gladiators]] are all raising their right or left arms, holding [[tridents]] and other weapons.<ref name=\"Winkler40\" />  Their salutation is a well-known [[Latin phrase]] quoted in [[Suetonius]], ''[[De Vita Caesarum]]'' (\"The Life of the Caesars\", or \"The Twelve Caesars\").<ref>[[Suetonius]], ''[[De Vita Caesarum]]: Divus Claudius'', 21.6</ref> Despite becoming widely popularised in later times, the phrase is unknown in Roman history aside from this isolated use, and it is questionable whether it was ever a customary salute, as is often believed.<ref>{{cite book|last=Baker|first=Alan|title=The gladiator: the secret history of Rome's warrior slaves|publisher=Ebury Press|year=2000|page=84|isbn=978-0-09-187880-1|url=https://books.google.com/?id=20YTAQAAIAAJ&q=%22morituri+te+salutant%22+Claudius&dq=%22morituri+te+salutant%22+Claudius&cd=7}}</ref> It was more likely to be an isolated appeal by desperate captives and criminals condemned to die.<ref name=\"kyle\">{{cite book|last=Kyle|first=Donald|title=Spectacles of death in ancient Rome  |publisher=Routledge|year=2001|page=94|isbn=978-0-415-24842-6|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1GYH63-fARUC&pg=PA94&lpg=PA94&dq=%22morituri+te+salutant%22+commodus&q=%22morituri%20te%20salutant%22%20commodus}}</ref>\n\n==19th\u201320th centuries United States==\n[[File:Students pledging allegiance to the American flag with the Bellamy salute.jpg|thumb|left|Children performing the [[Bellamy salute]] to the [[flag of the United States]]]]\nOn October 12, 1892, the [[Bellamy salute]] was demonstrated as the [[salute|hand gesture]] to accompany the [[Pledge of Allegiance (United States)|Pledge of Allegiance]] in the United States. The inventor of the saluting gesture was James B. Upham, junior partner and editor of ''The Youth's Companion''.<ref name=\"Miller\">{{cite book|last=Miller|first=Margarette S.|title=Twenty Three Words: A Biography of Francis Bellamy: Author of the Pledge of Allegiance|publisher=Natl Bellamy Award|year=1976|isbn=978-0-686-15626-0}}</ref>  Bellamy recalled Upham, upon reading the pledge, came into the posture of the salute, snapped his heels together, and said \"Now up there is the flag; I come to salute; as I say 'I pledge allegiance to my flag,' I stretch out my right hand and keep it raised while I say the stirring words that follow.\"<ref name=\"Miller\" />\n\nAs fascism took hold in Europe, controversy grew on the use of the Bellamy salute given its similarity to the Roman Salute.  When war broke out in 1939, the controversy intensified. School boards around the country revised the salute to avoid the similarity. There was a counter-backlash from the United States Flag Association and the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]], who felt it inappropriate for Americans to have to change the traditional salute because aliens had later adopted a similar gesture.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ellis |first1=Richard |title=To the Flag: The Unlikely History of the Pledge of Allegiance |date=2005 |publisher=University Press of Kansas |pages=113\u2013116 |edition=illustrated}}</ref>\n\nOn June 22, 1942, at the urging of the [[American Legion]] and the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]], Congress passed [[s: Public Law 77-623|Public Law 77-623]], which codified the etiquette used to display and pledge allegiance to the flag.  This included use of the Bellamy salute, specifically that the pledge \"be rendered by standing with the right hand over the heart; extending the right hand, palm upward, toward the flag at the words \u2018\u2018to the flag\u2019\u2019 and holding this position until the end, when the hand drops to the side.\"  Congress did not discuss or take into account the controversy over use of the salute. Congress later amended the code on December 22, 1942 when it passed [[s: Public Law 77-623|Public Law 77-829]].  Among other changes, it eliminated the Bellamy salute and replaced it with the stipulation that the pledge  \"be rendered by standing with the right hand over the heart.\"<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ellis |first1=Richard |title=To the Flag: The Unlikely History of the Pledge of Allegiance |date=2005 |publisher=University Press of Kansas |pages=116\u2013118 |edition=illustrated}}</ref>\n\n==Early 20th century in theatre and film==\nThe gesture, already established in the United States through the Bellamy salute, has been traced to the [[Broadway theater|Broadway]] production of the play ''[[Ben-Hur (play)|Ben-Hur]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler70\">Winkler (2009), p. 70</ref>  The play, based on [[Lew Wallace]]'s book ''[[Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ]]'', opened on Broadway in November 1899 and proved to be a great success.<ref name=\"Winkler71\">Winkler (2009), p. 71</ref>  Photographs show several scenes using the gesture, including one of Ben-Hur greeting a seated sheik and another of a small crowd so greeting Ben-Hur in his chariot.<ref name=\"Winkler73\">Winkler (2009), p. 73</ref>  Neither Wallace's novel nor text for the theatrical production mentions a raised arm salute.<ref name=\"Winkler73\" />  The salute was evidently added in keeping with the exaggerated style of acting in 19th century theater, which in turn influenced acting in the silent cinema.<ref name=\"Winkler75\">Winkler (2009), p. 75</ref>\n\nThe salute frequently occurs in early 20th century films set in antiquity, such as the American [[Ben-Hur (1907)|''Ben-Hur'' (1907)]] and the Italian ''[[Nerone (film)|Nerone]]'' (1908), although such films do not yet standardize it or make it exclusively Roman.<ref name=\"APA\" /> In ''Spartaco'' (1914), even the slave [[Spartacus]] uses it.<ref name=\"APA\" /> Later examples appear in ''[[Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ (1925 film)|Ben-Hur]]'' (1925) and in Cecil B. DeMille's ''[[The Sign of the Cross (1932 film)|Sign of the Cross]]'' (1932) and ''[[Cleopatra (1934 film)|Cleopatra]]'' (1934), although the execution of the gesture is still variable.<ref name=\"APA\">{{cite journal|last=Winkler|first=Martin|title=The Roman Salute on Film|journal=2003 APA Annual Meeting |publisher=The American Philological Association (APA)|issue=January 8, 2003|url=http://www.apaclassics.org/AnnualMeeting/03mtg/abstracts/Winkler.html}}</ref>\n\nOf special note is the use in [[Giovanni Pastrone]]'s colossal epic ''[[Cabiria]]'' (1914).<ref name=\"Winkler9495\">Winkler (2009), pp. 94\u201395</ref>  It's intertitles, character names, and movie title was attributed to Italian nationalist [[Gabriele d'Annunzio]], who was known as the \"poet-warrior\".<ref>Leeden (2001), p. 67</ref>  Inspired by the [[Italo-Turkish War]], in which Italy conquered the North African [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] province of [[Tripolitania]], Pastrone perused a politically volatile issue.<ref name=\"Solomon\">{{cite book|last=Solomon|first=Jon|title=The ancient world in the cinema|url=https://archive.org/details/ancientworldinci00solo|url-access=registration|publisher=Yale University Press|year=2001|edition=2, revised, illustrated|page=[https://archive.org/details/ancientworldinci00solo/page/48 48]|isbn=978-0-300-08337-8}}</ref> The film highlights Italy's Roman past and the \"monstrous\" nature of [[Carthage|Carthaginian]] society, which is contrasted with the \"nobility\" of Roman society.<ref>{{cite book|last=Wood|first=Mary P.|title=Italian cinema|publisher=Berg Publishers|year=2005|page=138|isbn=978-1-84520-162-3}}</ref> ''Cabiria'' was one of several films of the period that \"helped resuscitate a distant history that legitimized Italy's past and inspired its dreams\" and which \"delivered the spirit for conquest that seemed to arrive from the distant past\", thereby presaging the \"political rituals of fascism\", \"thanks&nbsp;... to its prime supporter and apostle, Gabriele d'Annunzio.\"<ref name=\"Brunetta\">{{cite book|last=Brunetta|first=Gian Piero |author2=Jeremy Parzen |title=The History of Italian Cinema: A Guide to Italian Film from Its Origins to the Twenty-First Century|publisher=Princeton University Press|year=2009|page=34|isbn=978-0-691-11988-5}}</ref>\n\nVariations on the salute occur throughout ''Cabiria'' on the part of Romans and Africans.<ref name=\"Winkler99\">Winkler (2009), p. 99</ref>  Scipio uses the gesture once.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  Fulvius Axilla, the story's fictitious hero, twice employs it as a farewell greeting to his hosts.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  The [[Numidian]] king [[Massinissa]], guest of the Carthaginian Hasdrubal, raises his right hand and is so greeted in return, once by the strongman [[Maciste]].<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  Princess [[Sophonisba]] and King [[Syphax]] mutually greet each other by raising their hands and declining their bodies.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />  The diversity of the gesture and the variety of nationalities who use it in ''Cabria'' is seen as further evidence that the salute is a modern invention, used in the film to highlight the exotic nature of antiquity.<ref name=\"Winkler99\" />\n\n==Adoption during the 20th century==\n\n=== Italy ===\n[[File:Hitlermusso2 edit.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Benito Mussolini]] and Hitler, Mussolini giving the Roman salute, 25 October 1936]]\nD'Annunzio, who had written the subtitles for the silent movie epic [[Cabiria]], appropriated the salute when he occupied [[Fiume]] in 1919.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\">Falasca-Zamponi (2000), p. 110</ref>  D'Annunzio has been described as the [[John the Baptist]] of [[Italian Fascism]],<ref name=\"Leeden\">Leeden (2001), p. xiii</ref> as virtually the entire ritual of Fascism was invented by D'Annunzio during his occupation of Fiume and his leadership of the \"[[Italian Regency of Carnaro]]\".<ref name=\"Paxton\">{{cite book|last=Paxton|first=Robert O.|title=The Anatomy of Fascism|publisher=Random House, Inc.|year=2005|edition=reprint|series=Vintage Series|pages=[https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism0000paxt/page/59 59\u201360]|chapter=Taking Root|isbn=978-1-4000-3391-1|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/anatomyoffascism0000paxt/page/59}}</ref>  Besides the Roman salute, these included the balcony address, the cries of ''\"[[Alala|Eia, eia, eia! Alal\u00e0]]!\"'', the dramatic and rhetorical dialogues with the crowd, and the use of religious symbols in new secular settings.<ref name=\"Leeden\" />\n\nLike other neo-Imperial rituals utilized by D'Annunzio, the salute became part of the [[Italian Fascism|Italian fascist]] movement's symbolic repertoire.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />  On January 31, 1923, the Ministry of Education instituted a ritual honoring the flag in schools using the Roman salute.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />  In 1925, as Mussolini began his fascitization of the state, the salute was gradually adopted by the regime, and by December 1, 1925 all state civil administrators were required to use it.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />\n\n[[Achille Starace]], the Italian [[National Fascist Party|Fascist Party]] secretary, pushed for measures to make the use of the Roman salute generally compulsory, denouncing [[handshake|hand shaking]] as [[bourgeois]]. He further extolled the salute as \"more hygienic, more aesthetic, and shorter.\" He also suggested that the Roman salute did not imply the necessity of taking off the hat unless one was indoors. By 1932, the salute was adopted as the substitute for the handshake.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110\" />  On August 19, 1933 the military was ordered to use the salute whenever an unarmed detachment of soldiers was called on to render military honors for the King or Mussolini.<ref name=\"NYTaug20\">{{cite news|url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F10B1EFB3E5B137A93C2AB1783D85F478385F9|title=Fascist Salute Is Adopted By Italian Armed Forces|last=Wireless|date=August 20, 1933|work=The New York Times|page=Page 1|accessdate=March 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe symbolic value of the gesture grew, and it was felt that the proper salute \"had the effect of showing the fascist man's decisive spirit, which was close to that of ancient Rome\".<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi110111\">Falasca-Zamponi (2000), pp. 110\u2013111</ref> The salute was seen to demonstrate the fascist's \"decisive spirit, firmness, seriousness, and acknowledgment and acceptance of the regime's hierarchical structure\".<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi112113\">Falasca-Zamponi (2000), pp. 112\u2013113</ref>  It was further felt that the correct physical gesture brought forth a change in character.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi113\">Falasca-Zamponi110 (2000), pp. 113</ref> A joke claimed, however, that the Fascist salute used one hand because Italians were tired of raising both hands to surrender during [[World War I]].<ref name=\"gunther1936\">{{cite book | url=https://openlibrary.org/works/OL16059565W/Inside_Europe | title=Inside Europe | publisher=Harper & Brothers | author=Gunther, John | year=1936 | pages=183}}</ref>\n\nThe bourgeois gesture was supposed to disappear from the view of Italians and not contaminate their daily life. In 1938, the party abolished handshaking in films and theater, and on November 21, 1938 the [[Ministry of Popular Culture]] issued orders banning the publishing of photographs showing people shaking hands. Even official photographs of visiting dignitaries were [[Photo manipulation|retouched]] to remove the image of their handshaking.<ref name=\"Falasca-Zamponi113\" />\n\n=== Germany ===\n{{Main|Nazi salute}}\nIn Germany, the salute, sporadically used by the [[Nazi Party]] (NSDAP) since 1923, was made compulsory within the movement in 1926.<ref name=\"Myth26\">Kershaw (2001), p. 26</ref> Called the [[Hitler]] salute (''Hitlergru\u00df''), it functioned both as an expression of commitment within the party and as a demonstrative statement to the outside world.<ref name=\"Tilman\">Tilman (2009), p. 55</ref>  Yet in spite of this demand for the outward display of obedience, the drive to gain acceptance did not go unchallenged, even within the movement.<ref name=\"Tilman\" /> Early objections focused on its resemblance to the Roman salute employed by Fascist Italy, and hence on it not being [[German folklore|Germanic]].<ref name=\"Tilman\" />  In response, efforts were made to establish its pedigree and invent a proper tradition after the fact.<ref name=\"Tilman\" />\n\nThe compulsory use of the Hitler salute for all public employees followed a directive issued by Reich [[Minister of the Interior]] [[Wilhelm Frick]] on July 13, 1933, one day before the ban on all non-Nazi parties.<ref name=\"Myth60\" >Kershaw (2001), p. 60</ref> The [[Wehrmacht]] refused to adopt the Hitler salute and was able for a time to maintain its own customs.<ref name=\"Tilman80\">Tilman (2009), pp. 80\u201382</ref>  The military were required to use the Hitler salute only while singing the [[Horst Wessel Lied]] and [[Deutschlandlied|German national anthem]], and in non-military encounters such as greeting members of the civilian government.<ref name=\"Tilman80\" />  Only after the [[July 20 Plot]] in 1944 were the military forces of the Third Reich ordered to replace the standard military salute with the Hitler salute.<ref name=\"Tilman82\">Tilman (2009), p. 82</ref>\n\n=== Elsewhere ===\n[[File:Metaxas-regime-greek-fascism.png|left|thumb|Salute in the [[Hellenic Parliament|Greek Parliament]], 1938]]\n[[File:Estonian League of Freedom Fighters - Vaps Movement - Roman salute 1.jpg|thumb|Estonian [[Vaps Movement]], 1933]]\n\nSimilar forms of salutes were adopted by various groups. Its use in France dates back to 1925, when the ''[[Jeunesses Patriotes]] (Patriotic Youth)'', a movement led by [[Pierre Taittinger]], would give the fascist salute at meetings while shouting \"Dictatorship!\".<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 40</ref> [[Marcel Bucard]]'s ''[[Mouvement Franciste]],'' founded in September 1933, adopted the salute as well as donning blue shirts and blue berets.<ref>Soucy (1997), p.&nbsp;38\u201339</ref>  ''[[Solidarit\u00e9 Fran\u00e7aise]]'' used the salute as well, though its leaders denied the movement was fascist.<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 71</ref>  By 1937, rivalry amongst French right wing parties sometimes caused confusion over salutes.<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 142</ref>  The [[Parti Populaire Fran\u00e7ais]], generally regarded as the most pro-Nazi of France's [[Collaborationism|collaborationist]] parties, adopted a variant of the salute that distinguished itself from others by slightly bending the hand and holding it at face level.<ref>Soucy (1997), p. 217</ref>\n\n[[File:SaudacaoIntegralista1935.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Brazilian Integralism|Integralists]] in [[Brazil]], 1935]]\nIn the early 1930s, the salute was used by members of the [[Estonia]]n nationalist right wing [[Vaps Movement]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U3L6H8eOIb0C&pg=PA1&dq=vaps+movement+nationalist#v=onepage&q=salute&f=false |title=The Radical Right in Interwar Estonia - Andres Kasekamp - Google Boeken |accessdate=2012-09-21|isbn=9780312225988 |last1=Kasekamp |first1=Andres |date=June 3, 2000 }}</ref> as well as the [[Brazilian Integralist Action]], who used to salute by raising one arm. The Brazilian form of the Salute was called \"Anau\u00ea\" \u2013 a word used as a salutation and as a cry by the Brazilian indigenous [[Tupi people|Tupi]] people, meaning \"you are my brother\".<ref name=\"Payne\">{{cite book|last=Payne|first=Stanley |title=A history of fascism, 1914\u20131945 |publisher=Routledge|year=1995|edition=2|page=345|chapter=Fascism outside Europe?|isbn=978-1-85728-595-6}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ante Pavelic Parlament.jpg|left|thumb|[[Ante Paveli\u0107]] greeting the [[Croatian parliament]] in February 1943]]\nIn [[Greece]] in 1936, when [[Ioannis Metaxas]] and his [[4th of August Regime]] took power, an almost identical salute was adopted \u2013 first by the [[National Youth Organisation (Greece)|National Youth Organization]] and later by the government as well as common people \u2013 and used even while fighting against Italy and Germany in WW2.\n\n[[File:Francoist demonstration in Salamanca.jpg|thumb|[[Francoist Spain|Francoist]] demonstration in [[Salamanca]], [[Spain]]]]\nIn Spain, on April 27, 1937, General [[Francisco Franco]] formally approved the salute in a decree which made it the official salutation to be used by all except the military, who would continue to use the traditional military salutes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Iy8rAAAAIBAJ&pg=2530,3492234&dq|title=Fascist Salute Adopted|date= April 27, 1937|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|page=10|accessdate=February 14, 2010}}</ref> This was repealed in September 1945.<ref>Decreto de la Presidencia del Consejo de Ministros derogando la obligatoriedad del saludo brazo en alto, de fecha 11 de septiembre de 1945, publicado en el B.O.E. n\u00fam, 257 con fecha 14 de septiembre de 1945.</ref>  When the Franco regime restored \"[[Marcha Real]]\" as the Spanish national anthem in 1942 and established unofficial [[Marcha Real#Franco lyrics|new lyrics]] for it, the first stanza referred to the fascist salute:  \"Alzad los brazos, hijos del pueblo espa\u00f1ol\" (\"Raise your arms, sons of the Spanish people\").  These lyrics remained part of the Spanish national anthem until 1978.<ref>{{cite news |last=Elkington |first=Mark |title=Divisive national anthem lyrics ditched |agency=Reuters |date=January 16, 2008 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/oddlyEnoughNews/idUSN1610811820080116 |accessdate=2016-08-24}}</ref>\n\nAfter a meeting with Mussolini, in December 1937, [[Kingdom of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] Prime Minister [[Milan Stojadinovi\u0107]] and chairman of [[Yugoslav Radical Union]] adopted a version of the salute as he took to styling himself as ''Vo\u0111a (Leader)''.<ref name=\"Bernard\">{{cite book|last=Singelton|first=Frederick Bernard|title=A short history of the Yugoslav peoples|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=1985|edition=2, illustrated|page=167|chapter=The kingdom of Yugoslavia|isbn=978-0-521-27485-2}}</ref><ref name=\"Benson\">{{cite book|last=Benson|first=Leslie|title=Yugoslavia: a concise history|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|year=2001|edition=illustrated|page=[https://archive.org/details/yugoslaviaconcis0000bens_i0i2/page/65 65]|chapter=Destruction of the First Yugoslavia|isbn=978-0-333-79241-4|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/yugoslaviaconcis0000bens_i0i2/page/65}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 1939, the salute by raising one arm was adopted in Romania under a statute promulgating the [[National Renaissance Front]].<ref name=\"Routledge\">{{cite book|last=Webb|first=Adrian|title=The Routledge companion to Central and Eastern Europe since 1919|publisher=Routledge|year=2008|series=Routledge companions to history|page=153|chapter=The Rise of Authoritianism 1919\u20131939|isbn=978-0-203-92817-2}}</ref> In Slovakia, the [[Hlinka Guard]]'s ''[[Na str\u00e1\u017e]]!'' (On guard!) consisted of a half-hearted compromise between a friendly wave and a salute with a straight raised arm.<ref name=\"Jelinek\">{{cite journal|last=Jelinek|first=Yeshayahu |year=1971|title=Storm-Troopers in Slovakia: The Rodobrana and the Hlinka Guard |journal=Journal of Contemporary History|publisher=Sage Publications|volume=6|issue=3|page=104|issn=0022-0094|oclc=49976309|jstor=259881|doi=10.1177/002200947100600307}}</ref>\n\n==Post World War II==\n\n===Italy===\nThe salute has been used many times by prominent individuals as well as groups of people since the war. Famed poet [[Ezra Pound]] used the salute in praise of his adopted country of Italy when he returned in 1958 after being released from an insane asylum in America.<ref name=\"NYT58\">{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=FA0E12FF3C5F117B93C2A8178CD85F4C8585F9 |title=Pound, in Italy, Gives Fascist Salute; Calls United States an 'Insane Asylum' |date=July 10, 1958 |work=The New York Times |page=56 |accessdate=March 1, 2010}}</ref> The salute was on display in the 1968 funeral for Mussolini's youngest daughter, Anna Maria Mussolini Negri.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/mem/archive/pdf?res=F10613F6345D147493C5AB178FD85F4C8685F9 |title=Mussolini's Followers Mourn Death of His Daughter|date=April 27, 1968|work=The New York Times |page=8 |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>  When the [[Italian Social Movement]] had its greatest electoral gains since the Second World War in June, 1971, crowds at the party headquarters cheered and gave the outstretched arm salute.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=A5kuAAAAIBAJ&pg=827,3985511 |title=Fascists Make Gains In Italian Elections |last=UPI |date= June 16, 1971 |publisher=Montreal Gazette |page=5 |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> On July 29, 1983, on the 100th anniversary of Mussolini's birth, thousands of black-shirted supporters chanted \"Duce! Duce!\" with their arms raised in the fascist salute on a march from his native village of [[Predappio]] in [[Romagna]] to the cemetery where he was buried.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SRUyAAAAIBAJ&pg=931,2855714 |title=Thousands Give Fascist Salute At Rally To Honor Mussolini |date=July 30, 1983 |publisher=Montreal Gazette |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref> On the eve of [[Silvio Berlusconi]]'s election victory in 1994, young supporters of [[Gianfranco Fini]] made the fascist salute while chanting \"Duce! Duce!\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/03/31/world/italy-s-neo-fascists-have-they-shed-their-past.html?pagewanted=1 |title=Italy's Neo-Fascists: Have They Shed Their Past?|last=COWELL|first=ALAN |date= March 31, 1994 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Italian [[association football|footballer]] [[Paolo Di Canio]] created controversy by twice using the gesture to salute [[S.S. Lazio]] fans, first in a match against archrivals [[A.S. Roma]] and then against [[A.S. Livorno Calcio]]  (a club inclined to leftist politics).<ref name=\"Kassimeris\">{{cite book |last=Kassimeris |first=Christos |title=European football in black and white: tackling racism in football |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=2008 |page=70 |isbn=978-0-7391-1960-0}}</ref> Di Canio received a one match game ban after the second event and was fined 7,000 euros, after which he was quoted as saying \"I will always salute as I did because it gives me a sense of belonging to my people [...] I saluted my people with what for me is a sign of belonging to a group that holds true values, values of civility against the standardisation that this society imposes upon us.\"<ref name=\"Nursey\">{{cite news|url=http://findarticles.com/p/news-articles/daily-mirror-the-london-uk/mi_8006/is_20051219/football-ll-di-canio-salute/ai_n40766979/ |title=Football: ll Di Canio new salute row |last=Nursey |first=James |date=December 19, 2005 |publisher=The Daily Mirror; London (UK) |accessdate=February 28, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>  His salute featured on unofficial merchandise sold outside [[Stadio Olimpico]] after the ban.<ref name=\"Kassimeris\" />  Di Canio has also expressed admiration for [[Benito Mussolini|Mussolini]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4158591.stm |title=Footballer's 'fascist salute' row |last=Duff |first=Mark |date=January 9, 2005 |publisher=BBC News  |accessdate=February 16, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/1506262/Im-a-fascist-not-a-racist-says-Paolo-di-Canio.html |title=I'm a fascist, not a racist, says Paolo di Canio |last=Fenton |first=Ben |date=December 24, 2005 |publisher=Telegraph |accessdate=February 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn June, 2009, [[Michela Vittoria Brambilla]], an Italian politician and businesswoman commonly described as a possible successor to [[Silvio Berlusconi]] for leadership of the Italian right, was caught in a controversy over her alleged use of the Roman salute, with calls for her to step down.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/feedarticle/8563250|title=Italy official in row over apparent fascist salute|last=AP foreign |date=June 17, 2009 |publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=March 15, 2010}}</ref>  She denied the accusation, stating \"I've never either done or thought of doing any gesture that is an apology of fascism, something toward which I've never showed any indulgence, let alone sympathy. And why should I have made a public display of such a despicable gesture shortly after I've been made a minister?\"<ref name=\"Guardian2009\" /> A video of the event was posted on the Web site of the newspaper ''La Repubblica'' that showed Brambilla extending her right arm upward in what appears to be a fascist salute.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\" />  Brambilla said she was just greeting the crowd.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\" />\n\n===Germany===\nUse of the salute and accompanying phrases has been forbidden by law in Germany since the end of World War II. [[Strafgesetzbuch section 86a|Section 86a]] of the German Penal Code provides for punishment of up to three years in prison for anyone using the salute, unless it is used for artistic, scientific, or educational purposes.<ref name=\"Tilman9495\">Tilman (2009), p.&nbsp;94\u201395</ref>\n\n===Greece===\nThe Greek nationalist party [[Golden Dawn (Greece)|Golden Dawn]] uses the Roman salute unofficially. Golden Dawn is accused by its opponents of being neo-Nazi, but the party denies this and claims that the salute is ancient Greek or Roman, and that it is used as a tribute to [[Ioannis Metaxas]] and his [[4th of August Regime]] which led Greece against the foreign occupation forces in WWII.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.madata.gr/epikairotita/politics/230568.html |title=\u039f \u03bd\u03b1\u03b6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03b1\u03c1\u03c7\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03cd \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2 |publisher=Madata.GR |date=2008-10-09 |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.ethnos.gr/article.asp?catid=22767&subid=2&pubid=63638177 | work=Ethnos | title=\u03a4\u03b1 \u03c0\u03b1\u03b9\u03b4\u03b9\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a7\u03af\u03c4\u03bb\u03b5\u03c1 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae \"\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ae\u03c2 \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae\u03c2\" | access-date=March 11, 2013 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606233050/http://www.ethnos.gr/article.asp?catid=22767&subid=2&pubid=63638177 | archive-date=June 6, 2014 | url-status=dead | df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news |url=http://tvxs.gr/news/ellada/nazistikos-xairetismos-sto-dimotiko-symboylio-tis-lamias-binteo | publisher=tvxs.gr |title=\u039d\u03b1\u03b6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf \u0394\u03b7\u03bc\u03bf\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03a3\u03c5\u03bc\u03b2\u03bf\u03cd\u03bb\u03b9\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u039b\u03b1\u03bc\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 |date=11 April 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.tovima.gr/politics/article/?aid=480509 |work=To Vima | title=\u0395\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03bd\u03b1\u03b6\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc \u03c7\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03b5\u03c4\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc \u03b7 \u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03ae \u0391\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae |date=22 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kyriakidou |first=Dina |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/11/12/us-greece-crisis-dawn-idUSBRE8AB09F20121112 |title=Special Report: Greece's far-right party goes on the offensive |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_12/11/2012_469572 |title=Far-right Golden Dawn goes on the offensive in Greece |publisher=ekathimerini.com |accessdate=2013-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130103181611/http://www.ekathimerini.com/4dcgi/_w_articles_wsite1_1_12/11/2012_469572 |archivedate=January 3, 2013 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keeptalkinggreece.com/2012/10/21/golden-dawn-chief-admits-his-party-uses-nazi-salute-and-demonstrates-it-with-a-gesture/ |title=Golden Dawn chief admits his party uses \"nazi salute\" and demonstrates it with a gesture |publisher=Keeptalkinggreece.com |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref>\n\n===The Levant===\nThe salute employed by certain groups and their supporters, like [[Hezbollah]], [[Fatah]],<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.theblaze.com/stories/2012/01/26/palestinians-use-nazi-sieg-heil-salute-during-fatah-celebration-in-lebanon/ |title=Theblaze.com |access-date=January 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180816142849/https://www.theblaze.com/stories/2012/01/26/palestinians-use-nazi-sieg-heil-salute-during-fatah-celebration-in-lebanon |archive-date=August 16, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> pro-Assad [[National Defence Force (Syria)|NDF]]<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SKM-Pxh-OUQ YouTube]</ref> and Assad supporters,<ref>[http://www.yourmiddleeast.com/news/syria-loyalists-rally-as-arabs-await-answer-on-deal_3612 Yourmiddleeast.com]</ref> the [[Syrian Social Nationalist Party]], and the [[Kataeb Party]],<ref>[http://www.thearabdigest.com/2012/08/lebanons-phalange-keeps-nazi-salute.html Thearabdigest.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141209051913/http://www.thearabdigest.com/2012/08/lebanons-phalange-keeps-nazi-salute.html |date=December 9, 2014 }}</ref> have often been confused with the Roman/Nazi salute, even though in many cases the salute is performed by a closed fist rather than the Roman/Nazi extended palm. Opposition fighters in Syria have also been filmed and documenting using it, or a variance thereof, on multiple occasions.<ref name=\"rocklandtimes.com\">[http://www.rocklandtimes.com/2013/04/05/benghazi-syria-arms-connection/ Rocklandtimes.com]</ref> From its use, a connection between Nazism and these groups is often alleged. Often these allegations are raised at the expense of the opposing groups, pro-Assad sympathizers alleging Nazi sympathies of the Opposition and vice versa.<ref name=\"rocklandtimes.com\"/> However, the oath of allegiance by the Lebanese army, and the salute to the flag uses the Roman salute - possibly influenced by Vichy France shortly before independence was officially gained in 1944 - still continues to be used by the state today.<ref name=\"Lebanese Army oath of allegience\">{{cite web|title=Timeframe 0:06 - 0:07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VBbYBZhbxpU|publisher=Lebanese Army}}</ref>\n\n===Portugal===\nIn Portugal the salute is still used today by the military to take their oath to the national flag, when they successfully complete the first phase of military instruction. Formed in front of the highest symbol of national sovereignty, the military in sense and attunement, raise their right arm pointed towards the flag and take their oath.{{fact|date=October 2019}}\n\n===South Africa===\nThe [[Afrikaner Weerstandsbeweging]], a neo-Nazi political party and paramilitary force known for its advocacy of an all-white Afrikaner ''[[Volkstaat]]'',<ref>\"Separation, even after apartheid; Many whites fear for life after [[Nelson Mandela|Mandela]],\" (21 June 2013) ''National Post'', Ontario</ref><ref>\"Extremists Steal Guns for S. Africa War\" (May 30, 1990), ''Elyria Chronicle Telegram''</ref> has utilized Nazi-style uniforms, flags, insignia, and salutes at meetings and public rallies.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QbvzZTB9O0k \"Eugene Terre'Blanche's Afrikaner Resistance Movement - Rally,\" youtube. See 0:40 for salutes.]</ref> Hundreds of supporters in 2010 delivered straight-arm salutes outside the funeral for its founder and former leader [[Eug\u00e8ne Terre'Blanche]], who was murdered by two black farm workers over an alleged wage dispute.<ref>{{Cite web|title=AWB leader Eugene Terreblanche's funeral in Ventersdorp, South Africa, in pictures|publisher=The Telegraph|accessdate=19 January 2018|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/picturegalleries/worldnews/7572063/AWB-leader-Eugene-Terreblanches-funeral-in-Ventersdorp-South-Africa-in-pictures.html?image=3}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=South African white supremacist Eugene Terreblanche laid to rest|publisher=The Telegraph|date=9 April 2010|accessdate=19 January 2018|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/southafrica/7571357/South-African-white-supremacist-Eugene-Terreblanche-laid-to-rest.html}}</ref>\n\n===Red Hand of Ulster Salute===\nThe Red Hand of Ulster Salute is a modified version of the Roman Salute in which the hand is raised vertically to symbolise the [[Red Hand of Ulster]].  It is used by some [[Rangers F.C.]] fans to show an affinity with the [[Ulster loyalism|Loyalist]] cause.  Its similarity to the Nazi salute has caused offence and the [[soccer|football]] club and its supporters' association have asked them not to use it.\n<ref name=BBCSport>\n{{cite web |author= |title=Uefa drops Rangers salute probe|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rangers/6383691.stm|publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=21 February 2007}} \n</ref>\n<ref name=HeraldScotland>\n{{cite web |author= |title=Outrage at 'Nazi salutes' by soldiers in front of Union Flag|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/13129109.Outrage_at__Nazi_salutes__by_soldiers_in_front_of_Union_Flag/|publisher=[[Herald Scotland]] |date=28 October 2013}} \n</ref>\n\n===Popular culture===\n[[File:11-04-06-LSJUMB-004.jpg|thumb|[[Stanford]] band members doing the Roman salute to the [[Spirit of Troy|marching band]] of rival USC.]]\nA large number of films made after World War II made the Roman salute a visual stereotype of a proto-fascist ancient Roman society.<ref name=\"Winkler151\">Winkler (2009), p. 151</ref>  In the 1951 film ''[[Quo Vadis (1951 film)|Quo Vadis]]'', [[Nero]]'s repeated use of the salute at mass rallies explicitly presents the Roman Empire as a Fascist military state.<ref name=\"Winkler14345\">Winkler (2009), p.&nbsp;143\u2013145</ref>  The movie provided other filmmakers of the time a model,<ref name=\"Winkler151\" /> with notable examples including ''[[Ben-Hur (1959 film)|Ben-Hur]]'',<ref name=\"Winkler155\">Winkler (2009), p. 155</ref> ''[[Spartacus (film)|Spartacus]]'',<ref>Winkler (2009), p.158</ref> ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'',<ref>Winkler (2009), p. 159</ref> and ''[[Caligula (film)|Caligula]]''. Not until ''[[Gladiator (2000 film)|Gladiator]]'' did the Roman epic return to the cinema.<ref name=\"Winkler164\">Winkler (2009), p. 164</ref>  In this movie, the salute is notably absent in most scenes, for example when [[Commodus]] enters Rome or when the Senate salutes the Emperor by head-bowing.<ref name=\"Winkler164\" />\n\nVariations on the salute also appear in [[neo-fascist]] contexts. For example, The Christian Falangist Party, founded in 1985, uses a \"[[Zogist salute|pectoral salute]]\", in which the right arm, bent at the elbow, is extended from the heart, palm down.<ref>Winkler (2009), p. 6</ref> This gesture was used in [[Fran\u00e7ois Truffaut]]'s [[1966 in film|1966 film]] ''[[Fahrenheit 451 (1966 film)|Fahrenheit 451]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler176\">Winkler (2009), p. 176</ref>  The film portrays a futuristic totalitarian society modeled after the fascist state, including black uniforms, [[book burning]]s, and thought control.<ref name=\"Winkler176\" />  In the ''[[Star Trek: The Original Series|Star Trek]]'' episode \"[[Mirror, Mirror (Star Trek: The Original Series)|Mirror, Mirror]]\", the salute begins with the right fist being placed over the heart, as in a pectoral salute, and then the arm is stretched out (usually up) before the body, open palm down, as in a traditional Roman salute.<ref name=\"Winkler169\">Winkler (2009), p. 169</ref>  In the episode, [[Captain Kirk]] and members of his crew are transported to a parallel universe in which the [[United Federation of Planets]] has been replaced by [[Mirror Universe (Star Trek)|an empire]] characterized by sadistic violence and torture, genocide, and unquestioning obedience to authority.<ref name=\"Winkler169\" /> A modified Roman salute is commonly used in the British-American series ''[[Rome (TV series)|Rome]]''.<ref name=\"Winkler174\">Winkler (2009), p. 174</ref>  Here the salute avoids similarity to the Fascist salute, as the series seeks not to depict these Romans as stereotypical conquerors.<ref name=\"Winkler174\" />  Therefore, the salute is not the familiar straight arm salute but rather resembles a pectoral salute, with the right hand is placed over the heart and then extended to the front of the body.<ref name=\"Winkler174\" />\n\n==See also==\n{{col-begin|width=50%}}{{col-break}}\n* [[1968 Olympics Black Power salute]]\n* [[1972 Olympics Black Power salute]]\n* ''[[Ave]]''\n* [[Ave Imperator, morituri te salutant]]\n* [[Bellamy salute]]\n* ''[[Bras d'honneur]]''\n{{col-break}}\n* ''[[Heil og s\u00e6l]]''\n* [[Olympic_symbols#Olympic_salute|Olympic salute]]\n* [[Quenelle (gesture)]] \n* [[Raised fist]]\n* [[Zogist salute]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n'''Bibliography'''\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{cite book|last=Allert|first=Tilman|author2=Translated by Jefferson Chase |title=The Hitler Salute: On the Meaning of a Gesture|publisher=Picador|date=April 2009|edition=Picador|isbn=978-0-312-42830-3}}\n* {{cite book|last=Falasca-Zamponi|first=Simonetta|title=Fascist spectacle: the aesthetics of power in Mussolini's Italy|publisher=University of California Press|year=2000|edition=illustrated|series=Studies on the history of society and culture|volume=28|isbn= 978-0-520-22677-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Kershaw|first=Ian|title=The \"Hitler myth\": Image and reality in the Third Reich|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|edition=2, reissue|isbn=978-0-19-280206-4}}\n* {{cite book|last=Ledeen|first=Michael Arthur|title=D'Annunzio: the first duce|publisher=Transaction Publishers|year=2001|edition=2, illustrated|isbn=978-0-7658-0742-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Parker|first=Noel|title=Portrayals of revolution: images, debates, and patterns of thought on the French Revolution|url=https://archive.org/details/portrayalsofrevo0000park|url-access=registration|publisher=SIU Press|year=1990|edition=illustrated|isbn=978-0-8093-1684-7}}\n* {{cite book|last=Soucy |first=Robert|title=French Fascism: The Second Wave, 1933\u20131939|publisher=Yale University Press|year=1997|edition=illustrated|isbn=978-0-300-07043-9}}\n* {{cite book|last=Winkler|first=Martin M.|title=The Roman Salute: Cinema, History, Ideology|publisher=Ohio State University Press|location=Columbus|year=2009|isbn=978-0-8142-0864-9}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Roman salutes}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121025144237/http://cache.daylife.com/imageserve/08ZibDD7rV1gS/340x.jpg President of Republic of China (Taiwan) Ma Ying Jeou giving Roman salute]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130527141450/http://www.tibet.net/en/flash/2004/0504/images/chen.jpg Former President of Republic of China (Taiwan) Chen Shui Bian giving Roman salute]\n* [http://farm1.static.flickr.com/134/337148966_e51e1d347d.jpg Officials in the Republic of China (Taiwan) being sworn in with Roman Salute]\n* [http://cheiron.humanities.mcmaster.ca/~trajan/images/hi/4.70.h.jpg Photograph] and [https://archive.is/20120524095058/http://cheiron.humanities.mcmaster.ca/~trajan/buildcartoon.cgi?13b \"cartoon view\" explanation] of [[Trajan's Column]], from [[McMaster University]] Humanities department\n*{{cite web|url=http://olympic-museum.de/poster/poster1924.htm |title=Paris 1924 \u2013 Jeux Olympiques |last=Droit |first=Jean |date= |work=From Olympic Games Museum |publisher=French Olympic Committee |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100829002316/http://olympic-museum.de/poster/poster1924.htm |archivedate=August 29, 2010 |df= }}. Poster from 1924 Olympics depicting [[Olympic salute]]\n\n{{Fascism}}\n{{Gestures}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roman Salute}}\n[[Category:Ancient Roman society|Salute]]\n[[Category:Greetings]]\n[[Category:Fascist symbols]]\n[[Category:Hand gestures]]\n[[Category:Gestures of respect]]\n[[Category:Salutes]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_salute"}
{"title_page": "Mount Hope, San Diego", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2013}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n'''Mount Hope''' is an [[ethnic group|ethnically]] diverse hilly neighborhood of the [[San Diego|City of San Diego, California]]. Located in the southeastern portion of the city, Mount Hope is named for the large municipal [[Mount Hope Cemetery (San Diego)|Mount Hope Cemetery]], which encompasses approximately {{Convert|115|acre|km2}} of the community. The neighborhood contains a mixture of residential, industrial, commercial, and cemetery uses.\n\n[[California State Route 94|State Route 94]] (Martin Luther King Jr. Freeway) is the northern boundary, [[Interstate 805]] is the eastern boundary, [[Interstate 15 in California|Interstate 15]] is the western boundary, and Imperial Avenue is the southern boundary. The major San Diego thoroughfare Market Street runs through this community.\n\nLocated within the community is an [[Unincorporated area#United States|unincorporated area]] encompassing the Greenwood Cemetery, a private cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandiego.gov/planning/community/profiles/southeasternsd/pdf/sesdcpplnnbhdelemcentralsec1.pdf |title=Central Sector |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Development Services Department, Planning Division |publisher=City of San Diego |accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref> Within Greenwood Cemetery, is the Cathedral Mausoleum which was built in 1919, which grew to the largest single building mausoleum in the world.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bissell |first1=Laurie |editor1-first=Thomas |editor1-last=Scharf |year=1982 |title=San Diego Cemeteries: A Brief Guide  |journal=The Journal of San Diego History |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages= |publisher=San Diego Historical Society |doi= |url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/82fall/cemeteries.htm |accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMount Hope is located within the fourth City Council District, currently represented by [[Marti Emerald]]. It is part of the Southeastern San Diego Planning Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.gov/citycouncil/cd9/neighborhoods/mounthope.shtml|title=Mount Hope|work=City Council District 9|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> It is served by the [[San Diego Unified School District]].\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|California}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods of San Diego}}\n\n{{Coord|32.71419|N|117.10761|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in San Diego]]\n\n\n{{SanDiegoCountyCA-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=April 2013}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=April 2019}}\n'''Mount Hope''' is an [[ethnic group|ethnically]] diverse hilly neighborhood of the [[San Diego|City of San Diego, California]]. Located in the southeastern portion of the city, Mount Hope is named for the large municipal [[Mount Hope Cemetery (San Diego)|Mount Hope Cemetery]], which encompasses approximately {{Convert|115|acre|km2}} of the community. The neighborhood contains a mixture of residential, industrial, commercial, and cemetery uses.\n\n[[California State Route 94|State Route 94]] (Martin Luther King Jr. Freeway) is the northern boundary, [[Interstate 805]] is the eastern boundary, [[Interstate 15 in California|Interstate 15]] is the western boundary, and Imperial Avenue is the southern boundary. The major San Diego thoroughfare Market Street runs through this community.\n\nLocated within the community is an [[Unincorporated area#United States|unincorporated area]] encompassing the Greenwood Cemetery, a private cemetery.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sandiego.gov/planning/community/profiles/southeasternsd/pdf/sesdcpplnnbhdelemcentralsec1.pdf |title=Central Sector |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Development Services Department, Planning Division |publisher=City of San Diego |accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref> Within Greenwood Cemetery, is the Cathedral Mausoleum which was built in 1919, which grew to the largest single building mausoleum in the world.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bissell |first1=Laurie |editor1-first=Thomas |editor1-last=Scharf |year=1982 |title=San Diego Cemeteries: A Brief Guide  |journal=The Journal of San Diego History |volume=28 |issue=4 |pages= |publisher=San Diego Historical Society |doi= |url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/82fall/cemeteries.htm |accessdate=April 29, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMount Hope is located within the ninth City Council District, currently represented by [[Marti Emerald]]. It is part of the Southeastern San Diego Planning Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sandiego.gov/citycouncil/cd9/neighborhoods/mounthope.shtml|title=Mount Hope|work=City Council District 9|accessdate=March 24, 2014}}</ref> It is served by the [[San Diego Unified School District]].\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|California}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Neighborhoods of San Diego}}\n\n{{Coord|32.71419|N|117.10761|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in San Diego]]\n\n\n{{SanDiegoCountyCA-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Spiritletters", "label": "safe", "comment": "fourth district as oppose to ninth", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Hope,_San_Diego"}
{"title_page": "Integral equation", "text_new": "{{for|equations of [[integer]] unknowns|Diophantine equation}}\n\nIn [[mathematics]], '''integral equations''' are equations in which an unknown [[function (mathematics)|function]] appears under an [[integral]] sign. \n\nThere is a close connection between [[differential equation|differential]] and integral equations, and some problems may be formulated either way. See, for example, [[Green's function]], [[Fredholm theory]], and [[Maxwell's equations]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe most basic type of integral equation is called a ''[[Fredholm integral equation|Fredholm equation]] of the first type'',\n:<math> f(x) = \\int_a^b K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt. </math>\n\nThe notation follows [[George B. Arfken|Arfken]]. Here {{mvar|\u03c6}} is an unknown function, {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}} is a known function,\nand {{mvar|K}} is another known function of two variables, often called the [[Kernel (integral operator)|kernel]] function. Note that the limits of integration are constant: this is what characterizes a Fredholm equation.\n\nIf the unknown function occurs both inside and outside of the integral, the equation is known as a ''Fredholm equation of the second type'',\n:<math> \\varphi(x) =  f(x)+ \\lambda \\int_a^b K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt. </math>\n\nThe parameter {{mvar|\u03bb}} is an unknown factor, which plays the same role as the [[eigenvalue]] in [[linear algebra]].\n\nIf one limit of integration is a variable, the equation is called a [[Volterra integral equation|Volterra equation]].  The following are called ''Volterra equations of the first and second types'', respectively,\n:<math> f(x) = \\int_a^x K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt </math>\n:<math> \\varphi(x) = f(x) + \\lambda \\int_a^x K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt. </math>\n\nIn all of the above, if the known function {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}} is identically zero, the equation is called a ''homogeneous integral equation''. If {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}} is nonzero, it is called an ''inhomogeneous integral equation''.\n\n==Numerical solution==\nIt is worth noting that integral equations often do not have an analytical solution, and must be solved numerically. An example of this is evaluating the [[EFIE|Electric-Field Integral Equation]] (EFIE) or [[Magnetic-Field Integral Equation]] (MFIE) over an arbitrarily shaped object in an electromagnetic scattering problem.\n\nOne method to solve numerically requires discretizing variables and replacing integral by a quadrature rule\n\n:<math> \\sum_{j=1}^n w_j K\\left (s_i,t_j \\right ) u(t_j)=f(s_i), \\qquad i=0, 1, \\cdots, n. </math>\n\nThen we have a system with {{mvar|n}} equations and {{mvar|n}} variables. By solving it we get the value of the {{mvar|n}} variables\n\n:<math>u(t_0),u(t_1),\\cdots,u(t_n).</math>\n\n==Classification==\nIntegral equations are classified according to three different dichotomies, creating eight different kinds:\n\n;Limits of integration\n* '''both fixed:''' [[Fredholm equation]]\n*'''one variable:''' [[Volterra equation]]\n;Placement of unknown function\n*'''only inside integral:''' first kind\n*'''both inside and outside integral:''' second kind\n;Nature of known function {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}}\n*'''identically zero:''' homogeneous\n*'''not identically zero:''' inhomogeneous\n\nIntegral equations are important in many applications. Problems in which integral equations are encountered include [[radiative transfer]], and the [[oscillation]] of a string, membrane, or axle. Oscillation problems may also be solved as [[differential equations]].\n\nBoth Fredholm and Volterra equations are linear integral equations, due to the linear behaviour of {{math|''\u03c6''(''x'')}} under the integral. A nonlinear Volterra integral equation has the general form:\n\n:<math> \\varphi(x) = f(x) + \\lambda \\int_a^x K(x,t)\\,F(x, t, \\varphi(t))\\,dt, </math>\nwhere {{mvar|F}} is a known function.\n\n==Wiener\u2013Hopf integral equations==\n{{main|Wiener\u2013Hopf method}}\n:<math> y(t) =\\lambda x(t)+\\int^{\\infty}_0 k(t-s)x(s)ds,\\qquad 0\\leq t<\\infty.</math>\n\nOriginally, such equations were studied in connection with problems in radiative transfer, and more recently, they have been related to the solution of boundary integral equations for planar problems in which the boundary is only piecewise smooth.\n\n==Power series solution for integral equations==\nIn many cases, if the Kernel of the integral equation is of the form {{math|''K''(''xt'')}} and the [[Mellin transform]] of {{math|''K''(''t'')}} exists, we can find the solution of the integral equation\n:<math>  g(s)=s \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dt K(st) f(t) </math>\nin the form of a power series\n:<math> f(t)= \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{a_{n}}{M(n+1)}t^{n} </math>\nwhere\n:<math> g(s)= \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}a_{n} s^{-n},  \\qquad M(n+1)=\\int_{0}^{\\infty}dtK(t)t^{n} </math>\nare the {{mvar|Z}}-transform of the function {{math|''g''(''s'')}}, and {{math|''M''(''n'' + 1)}} is the Mellin transform of the Kernel.\n\n{{see also|Liouville\u2013Neumann series}}\n\n==Integral equations as a generalization of eigenvalue equations==\nCertain homogeneous linear integral equations can be viewed as the continuum limit of [[Eigenvalue, eigenvector and eigenspace|eigenvalue equations]]. Using [[index notation]], an eigenvalue equation can be written as\n:<math> \\sum _j M_{i,j} v_j = \\lambda v_i</math>\nwhere {{math|'''M''' {{=}} [''M<sub>i,j</sub>'']}} is a matrix, {{math|'''v'''}} is one of its eigenvectors, and {{mvar|\u03bb}} is the associated eigenvalue.\n\nTaking the continuum limit, i.e., replacing the discrete indices {{mvar|i}} and {{mvar|j}} with continuous variables {{mvar|x}} and {{mvar|y}}, yields\n:<math> \\int K(x,y)\\varphi(y) \\mathrm{d}y = \\lambda \\varphi(x),</math>\nwhere the sum over {{mvar|j}} has been replaced by an integral over {{mvar|y}} and the matrix {{math|'''M'''}} and the vector {{math|'''v'''}} have been replaced by the ''kernel'' {{math|''K''(''x'', ''y'')}} and the [[eigenfunction]] {{math|''\u03c6''(''y'')}}. (The limits on the integral are fixed, analogously to the limits on the sum over {{mvar|j}}.) This gives a linear homogeneous Fredholm equation of the second type.\n\nIn general, {{math|''K''(''x'', ''y'')}} can be a [[Distribution (mathematics)|distribution]], rather than a function in the strict sense. If the distribution {{mvar|K}} has support only at the point {{math|''x'' {{=}} ''y''}}, then the integral equation reduces to a [[Eigenfunction|differential eigenfunction equation]].\n\nIn general, Volterra and Fredholm integral equations can arise from a single differential equation, depending on which sort of conditions are applied at the boundary of the domain of its solution.\n{{further|Fredholm theory}}\n\n== Applications ==\n\n*[[Actuarial science]] (ruin theory<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kent.ac.uk/smsas/personal/lb209/files/risk-notes-10.pdf|title=Lecture Notes on Risk Theory|date=2010}}</ref>)\n*[[Inverse problem|Inverse problems]]\n**[[Marchenko equation]] ([[inverse scattering transform]])\n* Options pricing under [[Jump diffusion|jump-diffusion]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sachs|first=E. W.|last2=Strauss|first2=A. K.|date=2008-11-01|title=Efficient solution of a partial integro-differential equation in finance|journal=Applied Numerical Mathematics|volume=58|issue=11|pages=1687\u20131703|doi=10.1016/j.apnum.2007.11.002|issn=0168-9274}}</ref>\n*[[Radiative transfer]]\n*[[Viscoelasticity]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Differential equation]]\n*[[Integro-differential equation]]\n*[[Ruin theory]]\n*[[Volterra integral equation]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*  Kendall E. Atkinson ''The Numerical Solution of integral Equations of the Second Kind''. Cambridge Monographs on Applied and Computational Mathematics, 1997.\n*  George Arfken and Hans Weber. ''Mathematical Methods for Physicists''. Harcourt/Academic Press, 2000.\n* [[Harry Bateman]] (1910) [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/94115#page/506/mode/1up History and Present State of the Theory of Integral Equations], ''Report'' of the [[British Association]].\n*  Andrei D. Polyanin and Alexander V. Manzhirov ''Handbook of Integral Equations''. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8493-2876-4}}.\n* [[E. T. Whittaker]] and [[G. N. Watson]]. ''A Course of Modern Analysis'' Cambridge Mathematical Library.\n*  M. Krasnov, A. Kiselev, G. Makarenko, ''Problems and Exercises in Integral Equations'', Mir Publishers, Moscow, 1971\n*{{Cite book | last1=Press | first1=WH | last2=Teukolsky | first2=SA | last3=Vetterling | first3=WT | last4=Flannery | first4=BP | year=2007 | title=Numerical Recipes: The Art of Scientific Computing | edition=3rd | publisher=Cambridge University Press |  location=New York | isbn=978-0-521-88068-8 | chapter=Chapter 19. Integral Equations and Inverse Theory | chapter-url=http://apps.nrbook.com/empanel/index.html#pg=986}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://eqworld.ipmnet.ru/en/solutions/ie.htm Integral Equations: Exact Solutions] at EqWorld: The World of Mathematical Equations.\n* [http://eqworld.ipmnet.ru/en/solutions/eqindex/eqindex-ie.htm Integral Equations: Index] at EqWorld: The World of Mathematical Equations.\n* {{springer|title=Integral equation|id=p/i051400}}\n*[https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/mathematics/18-307-integral-equations-spring-2006/index.htm Integral Equations] ([[MIT OpenCourseWare]])\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Integral equations| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|equations of [[integer]] unknowns|Diophantine equation}}\n\nIn [[mathematics]], '''integral equations''' are equations in which an unknown [[function (mathematics)|function]] appears under an [[integral]] sign. \n\nThere is a close connection between [[differential equation|differential]] and integral equations, and some problems may be formulated either way. See, for example, [[Green's function]], [[Fredholm theory]], and [[Maxwell's equations]].\n\n==Overview==\nThe most basic type of integral equation is called a ''[[Fredholm integral equation|Fredholm equation]] of the first type'',\n:<math> f(x) = \\int_a^b K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt. </math>\n\nThe notation follows [[George B. Arfken|Arfken]]. Here {{mvar|\u03c6}} is an unknown function, {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}} is a known function,\nand {{mvar|K}} is another known function of two variables, often called the [[Kernel (integral operator)|kernel]] function. Note that the limits of integration are constant: this is what characterizes a Fredholm equation.\n\nIf the unknown function occurs both inside and outside of the integral, the equation is known as a ''Fredholm equation of the second type'',\n:<math> \\varphi(x) =  f(x)+ \\lambda \\int_a^b K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt. </math>\n\nThe parameter {{mvar|\u03bb}} is an unknown factor, which plays the same role as the [[eigenvalue]] in [[linear algebra]].\n\nIf one limit of integration is a variable, the equation is called a [[Volterra integral equation|Volterra equation]].  The following are called ''Volterra equations of the first and second types'', respectively,\n:<math> f(x) = \\int_a^x K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt </math>\n:<math> \\varphi(x) = f(x) + \\lambda \\int_a^x K(x,t)\\,\\varphi(t)\\,dt. </math>\n\nIn all of the above, if the known function {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}} is identically zero, the equation is called a ''homogeneous integral equation''. If {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}} is nonzero, it is called an ''inhomogeneous integral equation''.\n\n==Numerical solution==\nIt is worth noting that integral equations often do not have an analytical solution, and must be solved numerically. An example of this is evaluating the [[EFIE|Electric-Field Integral Equation]] (EFIE) or [[Magnetic-Field Integral Equation]] (MFIE) over an arbitrarily shaped object in an electromagnetic scattering problem.\n\nOne method to solve numerically requires discretizing variables and replacing integral by a quadrature rule\n\n:<math> \\sum_{j=1}^n w_j K\\left (s_i,t_j \\right ) u(t_j)=f(s_i), \\qquad i=0, 1, \\cdots, n. </math>\n\nThen we have a system with {{mvar|n}} equations and {{mvar|n}} variables. By solving it we get the value of the {{mvar|n}} variables\n\n:<math>u(t_0),u(t_1),\\cdots,u(t_n).</math>\n\n==Classification==\nIntegral equations are classified according to three different dichotomies, creating eight different kinds:\n\n;Limits of integration\n* '''both fixed:''' [[Fredholm equation]]\n*'''one variable:''' [[Volterra equation]]\n;Placement of unknown function\n*'''only inside integral:''' first kind\n*'''both inside and outside integral:''' second kind\n;Nature of known function {{math|&thinsp;''f''&thinsp;}}\n*'''identically zero:''' homogeneous\n*'''not identically zero:''' inhomogeneous\n\nIntegral equations are important in many applications. Problems in which integral equations are encountered include [[radiative transfer]], and the [[oscillation]] of a string, membrane, or axle. Oscillation problems may also be solved as [[differential equations]].\n\nBoth Fredholm and Volterra equations are linear integral equations, due to the linear behaviour of {{math|''\u03c6''(''x'')}} under the integral. A nonlinear Volterra integral equation has the general form:\n\n:<math> \\varphi(x) = f(x) + \\lambda \\int_a^x K(x,t)\\,F(x, t, \\varphi(t))\\,dt, </math>\nwhere {{mvar|F}} is a known function.\n\n==Wiener\u2013Hopf integral equations==\n{{main|Wiener\u2013Hopf method}}\n:<math> y(t) =\\lambda x(t)+\\int^{\\infty}_0 k(t-s)x(s)ds,\\qquad 0\\leq t<\\infty.</math>\n\nOriginally, such equations were studied in connection with problems in radiative transfer, and more recently, they have been related to the solution of boundary integral equations for planar problems in which the boundary is only piecewise smooth.\n\n==Power series solution for integral equations==\nIn many cases, if the Kernel of the integral equation is of the form {{math|''K''(''xt'')}} and the [[Mellin transform]] of {{math|''K''(''t'')}} exists, we can find the solution of the integral equation\n:<math>  g(s)=s \\int_{0}^{\\infty} dt K(st) f(t) </math>\nin the form of a power series\n:<math> f(t)= \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}\\frac{a_{n}}{M(n+1)}t^{n} </math>\nwhere\n:<math> g(s)= \\sum_{n=0}^{\\infty}a_{n} s^{-n},  \\qquad M(n+1)=\\int_{0}^{\\infty}dtK(t)t^{n} </math>\nare the {{mvar|Z}}-transform of the function {{math|''g''(''s'')}}, and {{math|''M''(''n'' + 1)}} is the Mellin transform of the Kernel.\n\n{{see also|Liouville\u2013Neumann series}}\n\n==Integral equations as a generalization of eigenvalue equations==\nCertain homogeneous linear integral equations can be viewed as the continuum limit of [[Eigenvalue, eigenvector and eigenspace|eigenvalue equations]]. Using [[index notation]], an eigenvalue equation can be written as\n:<math> \\sum _j M_{i,j} v_j = \\lambda v_i</math>\nwhere {{math|'''M''' {{=}} [''M<sub>i,j</sub>'']}} is a matrix, {{math|'''v'''}} is one of its eigenvectors, and {{mvar|\u03bb}} is the associated eigenvalue.\n\nTaking the continuum limit, i.e., replacing the discrete indices {{mvar|i}} and {{mvar|j}} with continuous variables {{mvar|x}} and {{mvar|y}}, yields\n:<math> \\int K(x,y)\\varphi(y) \\mathrm{d}y = \\lambda \\varphi(x),</math>\nwhere the sum over {{mvar|j}} has been replaced by an integral over {{mvar|y}} and the matrix {{math|'''M'''}} and the vector {{math|'''v'''}} have been replaced by the ''kernel'' {{math|''K''(''x'', ''y'')}} and the [[eigenfunction]] {{math|''\u03c6''(''y'')}}. (The limits on the integral are fixed, analogously to the limits on the sum over {{mvar|j}}.) This gives a linear homogeneous Fredholm equation of the second type.\n\nIn general, {{math|''K''(''x'', ''y'')}} can be a [[Distribution (mathematics)|distribution]], rather than a function in the strict sense. If the distribution {{mvar|K}} has support only at the point {{math|''x'' {{=}} ''y''}}, then the integral equation reduces to a [[Eigenfunction|differential eigenfunction equation]].\n\nIn general, Volterra and Fredholm integral equations can arise from a single differential equation, depending on which sort of conditions are applied at the boundary of the domain of its solution.\n{{further|Fredholm theory}}\n\n== Applications ==\n\n*[[Actuarial science]] (ruin theory<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kent.ac.uk/smsas/personal/lb209/files/risk-notes-10.pdf|title=Lecture Notes on Risk Theory|date=2010}}</ref>)\n*[[Inverse problem|Inverse problems]]\n**[[Marchenko equation]] ([[inverse scattering transform]])\n* Options pricing under [[Jump diffusion|jump-diffusion]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sachs|first=E. W.|last2=Strauss|first2=A. K.|date=2008-11-01|title=Efficient solution of a partial integro-differential equation in finance|journal=Applied Numerical Mathematics|volume=58|issue=11|pages=1687\u20131703|doi=10.1016/j.apnum.2007.11.002|issn=0168-9274}}</ref>\n*[[Radiative transfer]]\n*[[Viscoelasticity]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Differential equation]]\n*[[Integro-differential equation]]\n*[[Ruin theory]]\n*[[Volterra integral equation]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n*  Kendall E. Atkinson ''The Numerical Solution of integral Equations of the Second Kind''. Cambridge Monographs on Applied and Computational Mathematics, 1997.\n*  George Arfken and Hans Weber. ''Mathematical Methods for Physicists''. Harcourt/Academic Press, 2000.\n* [[Harry Bateman]] (1910) [https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/94115#page/506/mode/1up History and Present State of the Theory of Integral Equations], ''Report'' of the [[British Association]].\n*  Andrei D. Polyanin and Alexander V. Manzhirov ''Handbook of Integral Equations''. CRC Press, Boca Raton, 1998. {{ISBN|0-8493-2876-4}}.\n* [[E. T. Whittaker]] and [[G. N. Watson]]. ''A Course of Modern Analysis'' Cambridge Mathematical Library.\n*  M. Krasnov, A. Kiselev, G. Makarenko, ''Problems and Exercises in Integral Equations'', Mir Publishers, Moscow, 1971\n*{{Cite book | last